{"title_page": "A Gentleman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Gentleman: Sundar, Susheel, Risky\n| image          = A_Gentleman.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Raj Nidimoru and Krishna D.K.|Raj & D.K.]]\n| producer       = [[Fox Star Studios]]\n| writer         = '''Story:'''<br>[[Raj Nidimoru and Krishna D.K.|Raj & D.K.]]<br>Sita Menon<br>'''Screenplay:'''<br>[[Raj Nidimoru and Krishna D.K.|Raj & D.K.]]<br>'''Dialogues:'''<br>Sumit Batheja\n| starring       = [[Sidharth Malhotra]]<br />[[Jacqueline Fernandez]]<br />[[Darshan Kumaar]]<br />[[Suniel Shetty]]\n| music          = [[Sachin-Jigar]]\n| cinematography = Roman Jakobi\n| editing        = Aarif Sheikh\n| studio         = [[Fox Star Studios]]\n| distributor    = Fox Star Studios\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|08|25|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| budget         = {{INR}}60crore<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=3589|title=Magilche neruppu da - Movie - Box Office India|website=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{INR}}38.3 [[crores]]<ref name=\"BH gross\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-breakup-gentleman/ |title=Box Office: Worldwide Collections and Day wise breakup of A Gentleman |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |date=2017-08-26 |accessdate=2017-09-29}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''A Gentleman: Sundar, Susheel, Risky''''' is a 2017 Indian [[Action film|action]] [[comedy film]], written and directed by  [[Raj Nidimoru and Krishna D.K.]]<ref name=\"bb2\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sidharth-malhotra-jacqueline-fernandez-start-shooting-for-their-action-film-bang-bang-2-2790249/ |title=Sidharth Malhotra, Jacqueline Fernandez start shooting for their action film |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref> The film features [[Sidharth Malhotra]] in a dual role opposite [[Jacqueline Fernandez]], while [[Suniel Shetty]] plays the antagonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-save-the-date-sidharth-malhotra-and-jacqueline-fernandez-starrer-reload-to-release-on-august-25-2017-2282867 |title=Save The Date! Sidharth Malhotra and Jacqueline Fernandez starrer 'Reload' to release on August 25, 2017 on Ganesh Chaturthi weekend! &#124; Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis |website=Dnaindia.com |date=2016-12-14 |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref>\n\n''A Gentleman'' was theatrically released in India on 25 August 2017. It received moderate reviews from critics, and failed to recoup its {{INRConvert|600|m}} investment, grossing {{INRConvert|400|m}}.\n\n==Plot==\nIn the present day, 2017,Gaurav Kapoor ([[Sidharth Malhotra]]), based in suburban [[Miami]], plans to marry his colleague Kavya ([[Jacqueline Fernandez]]), who happens to be the woman of his dreams, but she prefers a man who is more adventurous and risk-loving.\n\nRunning parallel to his story , is the story of clandestine spy Rishi Purohit ([[Sidharth Malhotra]]), who is seen to have been trying to extract some crucial substance from the Chinese Embassy in Bangkok. However, when a co-spy, Yakub ([[Darshan Kumaar]]), shoots down an innocent civilian, the dishonest move enrages Rishi. Nonetheless, he returns to Mumbai, where it is revealed that he works for Unit X, a spy organisation headed by Colonel Vijay Saxena ([[Suniel Shetty]]). Rishi explains to Col. Vijay that he can't continue with such routines, and that he wants to start life afresh. Col. Vijay asks him to perform one last job for him, and this involves spying on a minister who Col. Vijay claims to be corrupt and wants to blackmail, and copying data from his cellphone into a hard drive which is wanted by Col. Vijay. Rishi does save contents into the hard drive, but Col. Vijay, having decided that Rishi is useless, instructs Yakub through a text message to kill him. Rishi senses the suspicion, and fights off Yakub and the other spies. Yakub manages to shoot Rishi, destroying the hard drive, but Rishi escapes.\n\nGaurav tries to hang out with Kavya on a date, and also meets her parents, who consider getting him married to Kavya. Meanwhile, he is ordered by his boss to visit Mumbai to close a business deal. Rewinding to Rishi's life, he is shown meeting a man named Gaurav Kapoor, who works in a cyber firm in Mumbai, and has important data about the minister's connections. When Gaurav is murdered by Yakub on account of being a liability, Rishi decides to adopt Gaurav's identity to successfully escape from Yakub after his last mission. This leads to his present-day life in 2017 as Gaurav in a Miami software company meaning Gaurav and Rishi are the same person and the events leading up to his new life took place five years earlier in 2012.\n\nAfter being unintentionally recorded in a viral video and recognised by the members of Unit X, Gaurav is soon attacked by Koko, an associate of Unit X's local contact Jignesh. He is forced to abduct and hide Koko in his car, which is noticed by his friend Dixit ([[Hussain Dalal]]), who tries to help him and unintentionally kills Koko in the struggle. Yakub and other Unit X agents track Gaurav down, and confront him, where he finally confesses, as Rishi, that he needed a life. He is knocked down unconscious, and soon finds himself handcuffed with Kavya who had stopped by his house. Gaurav uses his skills to escape with Kavya from the trouble, and ends up confessing to her that he is a retired covert operations specialist. Kavya berates him, but takes pity on him when she notices his bloody stab wound. The two make love. Later that night, the two find themselves under fire after Unit X agents, headed by Yakub, raid the motel they are hiding in. Rishi hatches a quick scheme to retrieve the data, since the hard drive is damaged, and convinces Yakub to work with him on their final mission.\n\nRishi executes the heist with success, but security guards take notice and begin chasing Rishi. Yakub aborts the operation and abandons him. They meet at Rishi's house, where Rishi kills most of Yakub's henchmen with the help of Kavya. However, Rishi spares Yakub and two of his thugs and orders him to leave his house. Driving away in Rishi's car, Yakub realises that the hard drive Rishi gave is blank, and the car's trunk contains Koko's corpse. Dixit, working with Rishi, crashes into their car in a [[side collision]], and police arriving on the scene discover the body. Yakub and his thugs are killed by the cops as they open fire. Col. Vijay visits Rishi's house to confront him, but is killed in an explosion planned by Rishi. This neutralises Unit X, and Rishi and Kavya soon leave the city with new identities of Hemant and Pooja Khanna.\n\nA mid-credits scene shows Dixit buying machine guns from a local gun store in Miami before putting on a [[hoodie]] and walking away.\n\n==Cast==\n<!--As this film has Sequel been released, additions to this section must be sourced, per WP:CRYSTAL-->\n* [[Sidharth Malhotra]] as Rishi Purohit/ Gaurav Kapoor  \n* [[Jacqueline Fernandez]] as Kavya Rishi Purohit\n* [[Suniel Shetty]] as Colonel Vijay Kumar Saxena\n* [[Darshan Kumaar]] as Yakub Sabri\n* [[Hussain Dalal]] as Arth Dixit, Rishi's friend and colleague\n* [[Rajit Kapur]] as Kavya's father\n* [[Supriya Pilgaonkar]] as Kavya's mother\n* [[Amit Mistry]] as Jignesh Patel\n* [[Sijoy Varghese]] as Ramachandra Rao\n* [[Shaheed Woods]] as Koko\n* [[Kushal Punjabi]] as Willy\n* Zachary Coffin as CEO Jim\n* Hemant Koumar as Robbie\n* Nikita Sachdev as Nikki\n* [[Shahid Kapoor]] Gaurav Kapoor Plastic Before Surgery\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n\nSiddharth Anand has stated that the movie was originally envisioned as a sequel to the 2014 film [[Bang Bang!]] However, it was later clarified in an interview that the movie would be a standalone.<ref name=sequel>{{cite web | url = http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141012/entertainment-bollywood/article/bang-bang-sequel | title = Bang Bang sequel on?|website=[[Deccan Chronicle]] | date = 12 October 2014 | accessdate = 12 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/bang-bang%E2%80%99-a-sequel-in-the-pipeline_1481537.html | title = 'Bang Bang': A sequel in the pipeline? |website=Zeenews.india.com| date = 8 October 2014 | accessdate = 12 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ibtimes.co.in/hrithik-roshan-katrina-kaifs-bang-bang-have-sequel-soon-610704 | title = Hrithik Roshan, Katrina Kaif's 'Bang Bang' to have a Sequel Soon? |website=Ibtimes.co.in| date = 7 October 2014 | accessdate = 12 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming began in mid-2016 under the working title ''Reloaded''.<ref name=\"bb2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/sidharth-malhotra-gets-injured-on-reloaded-sets-4428364/ |title=Sidharth Malhotra gets injured on Reload sets |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date=2016-12-15 |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref> In September 2016, it was reported that the international shooting schedule of ''A Gentleman: Sundar, Susheel, Risky'' had been canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-international-shooting-schedule-of-bang-bang-reloaded-scrapped-2254978 |title=International shooting schedule of 'Bang Bang Reloaded' scrapped &#124; Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis |website=Dnaindia.com |date=2016-09-14 |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref> Later it was revealed by a close source that \"...there will be another long schedule in December but the location is yet to be finalised. It could be in Europe.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/sidharth-malhotra-and-jacqueline-fernandezs-reloaded-to-be-shot-in-thailand-now-15509.html |title=Sidharth Malhotra and Jacqueline Fernandez\u00e2\u20ac\u2122s Reloaded to be shot in Thailand now |website=Filmfare.com |date=2016-09-09 |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/a-gentleman-first-look-sidharth-malhotra-jacqueline-fernandez-starrer-will-pique-your-interest/articleshow/59001956.cms |title=A Gentleman's first look out now.|website=timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2017-06-05 |accessdate=2017-06-06}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Gentleman: Sundar, Susheel, Risky\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 17 August 2017\n| recorded   = 2016\u20132017\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack|Feature film Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 16:15\n| language   = [[Hindi]]\n| label      = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Bhoomi (film)|Bhoomi]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = [[Hindi Medium]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc = {{External media\n| audio1      = {{YouTube|U_OAyJNQ3-A|Official Audio Jukebox}}\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = A Gentleman\n | type        = Soundtrack\n | single1     = Disco Disco\n | single1date = 20 July 2017\n | single2     = Baat Ban Jaye\n | single2date = 27 July 2017\n | single3     = Chandalekha\n | single3date = 4 August 2017\n | single4     = Bandook Meri Laila\n | single4date = 16 August 2017\n}}\n}}\nThe music of the film is composed by [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]] while the lyrics have been penned by Vayu and [[Priya Saraiya]]. Its first song titled as \"Disco Disco\" sung by [[Benny Dayal]] and [[Shirley Setia]] was released on 17 July 2017.  The second song to be released was \"Bandook Meri Laila\" which is sung by [[Ash King]] and [[Jigar Saraiya]] and rapped by [[Raftaar (rapper)|Raftaar]] and [[Sidharth Malhotra]] was released on 24 July 2017. The song marks Malhotra's singing debut. It was the most popular song on the album. The third song \"Baat Ban Jaye\" sung by [[Siddharth Basrur]] and [[Priya Saraiya]] was released on 5 August 2017. The fourth song was a romantic one \"Laagi Na Choote which was also a chartbuster after Bandook Meri Laila. It was released on 13 August 2017.The last but not the least song titled as \"Chandralekha\" which is sung by [[Vishal Dadlani]] and [[Jonita Gandhi]] was released on 24 August 2017. The soundtrack which includes five songs was released on 24 August 2017 by [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]].\n{{tracklist\n| headline =Track listing \n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length=16:15\n| title1 = Disco Disco\n| extra1 = [[Benny Dayal]], [[Shirley Setia]]\n| lyrics1 = Vayu\n| all_music = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| length1 = 2:47\n| title2 = Baat Ban Jaye\n| extra2 = [[Siddharth Basrur]], [[Priya Saraiya]]\n| lyrics2 = [[Priya Saraiya]]\n| length2 = 3:12\n| title3 = Chandralekha\n| extra3 = [[Vishal Dadlani]], [[Jonita Gandhi]]\n| lyrics3 = Vayu\n| length3 = 3:12\n| title4 = Laagi Na Choote\n| lyrics4 = Priya Saraiya\n| extra4 = [[Arijit Singh]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]]\n| length4 = 3:30\n| title5 = Bandook Meri Laila\n| length5 = 3:34\n| extra5 = [[Ash King]], [[Jigar Saraiya]] Rap: [[Raftaar (rapper)|Raftaar]], [[Sidharth Malhotra]]\n| lyrics5 = Vayu\n}}\n\n== Critical reception ==\n\n===Domestic===\n[[Times of India]] rated the film 3.5 stars out of 5 and concluded, \"The film would have been a perfect entertainer had it held its cards closer to its chest. However, it still has plenty bang for your buck.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/a-gentleman/movie-review/60219419.cms\n |title=A Gentleman Movie Review |accessdate=2017-08-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Hindustan Times]] gave the film 3 out of 5, saying, \"A Gentleman is not a flawless film but Raj and DK have managed to narrate the  story in their own quirky style and their dialogues and the screenplay make it fun to watch.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/a-gentleman-movie-review-sidharth-malhotra-jacqueline-film-is-sundar-but-is-it-susheel/story-kQSSECk7BfVEUtzHw7xWFL.html |title=A Gentleman movie review: Sidharth Malhotra takes you on a risky ride, but it's worth it |accessdate=2017-08-25}}</ref>\n\n===UAE===\nThe movie released on 24 August in Dubai, UAE. Dollz in Dubai gave it 3.5 out of 5 stars calling it a masala entertainer and wrote \"It\u2019s a big step for Siddharth Malhotra who manages to carry the film and commands the screen with his presence. Yes, he\u2019s good looking but he pulls off the action sequences really well.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dollzindubai.com/2017/08/25/movie-review-a-gentleman-sundar-susheel-risky/|title=Movie Review: A Gentleman \u2013 Sundar, Susheel, Risky|last=+Ekta|date=2017-08-24|website=Dollz in Dubai|access-date=2017-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5613834|A Gentleman}}\n*[https://www.facebook.com/AGentlemanTheMovie/ A Gentleman Official]  at [[Facebook]]\n* [http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/a-gentleman/ A Gentleman] at [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gentleman, A}}\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s action adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s spy comedy films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian action comedy films]]\n[[Category:Indian action adventure films]]\n[[Category:Indian spy comedy films]]\n[[Category:Indian adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:Fox Star Studios films]]\n[[Category:Masala films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Gentleman: Sundar, Susheel, Risky\n| image          = A_Gentleman.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Raj Nidimoru and Krishna D.K.|Raj & D.K.]]\n| producer       = [[Fox Star Studios]]\n| writer         = '''Story:'''<br>[[Raj Nidimoru and Krishna D.K.|Raj & D.K.]]<br>Sita Menon<br>'''Screenplay:'''<br>[[Raj Nidimoru and Krishna D.K.|Raj & D.K.]]<br>'''Dialogues:'''<br>Sumit Batheja\n| starring       = [[Sidharth Malhotra]]<br />[[Jacqueline Fernandez]]<br />[[Darshan Kumaar]]<br />[[Suniel Shetty]]\n| music          = [[Sachin-Jigar]]\n| cinematography = Roman Jakobi\n| editing        = Aarif Sheikh\n| studio         = [[Fox Star Studios]]\n| distributor    = Fox Star Studios\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|08|25|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| budget         = {{INR}}60crore<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=3589|title=Magilche neruppu da - Movie - Box Office India|website=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{INR}}38.3 [[crores]]<ref name=\"BH gross\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-breakup-gentleman/ |title=Box Office: Worldwide Collections and Day wise breakup of A Gentleman |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |date=2017-08-26 |accessdate=2017-09-29}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''A Gentleman: Sundar, Susheel, Risky''''' is a 2017 Indian [[Action film|action]] [[comedy film]], written and directed by  [[Raj Nidimoru and Krishna D.K.]]<ref name=\"bb2\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sidharth-malhotra-jacqueline-fernandez-start-shooting-for-their-action-film-bang-bang-2-2790249/ |title=Sidharth Malhotra, Jacqueline Fernandez start shooting for their action film |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref> The film features [[Sidharth Malhotra]] in a dual role opposite [[Jacqueline Fernandez]], while [[Suniel Shetty]] plays the antagonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-save-the-date-sidharth-malhotra-and-jacqueline-fernandez-starrer-reload-to-release-on-august-25-2017-2282867 |title=Save The Date! Sidharth Malhotra and Jacqueline Fernandez starrer 'Reload' to release on August 25, 2017 on Ganesh Chaturthi weekend! &#124; Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis |website=Dnaindia.com |date=2016-12-14 |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref>\n\n''A Gentleman'' was theatrically released in India on 25 August 2017. It received moderate reviews from critics, and failed to recoup its {{INRConvert|600|m}} investment, grossing {{INRConvert|400|m}}.\n\n==Plot==\nIn the present day, 2017,Gaurav Kapoor ([[Sidharth Malhotra]]), based in suburban [[Miami]], plans to marry his colleague Kavya ([[Jacqueline Fernandez]]), who happens to be the woman of his dreams, but she prefers a man who is more adventurous and risk-loving.\n\nRunning parallel to his story , is the story of clandestine spy Rishi Purohit ([[Sidharth Malhotra]]), who is seen to have been trying to extract some crucial substance from the Chinese Embassy in Bangkok. However, when a co-spy, Yakub ([[Darshan Kumaar]]), shoots down an innocent civilian, the dishonest move enrages Rishi. Nonetheless, he returns to Mumbai, where it is revealed that he works for Unit X, a spy organisation headed by Colonel Vijay Saxena ([[Suniel Shetty]]). Rishi explains to Col. Vijay that he can't continue with such routines, and that he wants to start life afresh. Col. Vijay asks him to perform one last job for him, and this involves spying on a minister who Col. Vijay claims to be corrupt and wants to blackmail, and copying data from his cellphone into a hard drive which is wanted by Col. Vijay. Rishi does save contents into the hard drive, but Col. Vijay, having decided that Rishi is useless, instructs Yakub through a text message to kill him. Rishi senses the suspicion, and fights off Yakub and the other spies. Yakub manages to shoot Rishi, destroying the hard drive, but Rishi escapes.\n\nGaurav tries to hang out with Kavya on a date, and also meets her parents, who consider getting him married to Kavya. Meanwhile, he is ordered by his boss to visit Mumbai to close a business deal. Rewinding to Rishi's life, he is shown meeting a man named Gaurav Kapoor, who works in a cyber firm in Mumbai, and has important data about the minister's connections. When Gaurav is murdered by Yakub on account of being a liability, Rishi decides to adopt Gaurav's identity to successfully escape from Yakub after his last mission. This leads to his present-day life in 2017 as Gaurav in a Miami software company meaning Gaurav and Rishi are the same person and the events leading up to his new life took place five years earlier in 2012.\n\nAfter being unintentionally recorded in a viral video and recognised by the members of Unit X, Gaurav is soon attacked by Koko, an associate of Unit X's local contact Jignesh. He is forced to abduct and hide Koko in his car, which is noticed by his friend Dixit ([[Hussain Dalal]]), who tries to help him and unintentionally kills Koko in the struggle. Yakub and other Unit X agents track Gaurav down, and confront him, where he finally confesses, as Rishi, that he needed a life. He is knocked down unconscious, and soon finds himself handcuffed with Kavya who had stopped by his house. Gaurav uses his skills to escape with Kavya from the trouble, and ends up confessing to her that he is a retired covert operations specialist. Kavya berates him, but takes pity on him when she notices his bloody stab wound. The two make love. Later that night, the two find themselves under fire after Unit X agents, headed by Yakub, raid the motel they are hiding in. Rishi hatches a quick scheme to retrieve the data, since the hard drive is damaged, and convinces Yakub to work with him on their final mission.\n\nRishi executes the heist with success, but security guards take notice and begin chasing Rishi. Yakub aborts the operation and abandons him. They meet at Rishi's house, where Rishi kills most of Yakub's henchmen with the help of Kavya. However, Rishi spares Yakub and two of his thugs and orders him to leave his house. Driving away in Rishi's car, Yakub realises that the hard drive Rishi gave is blank, and the car's trunk contains Koko's corpse. Dixit, working with Rishi, crashes into their car in a [[side collision]], and police arriving on the scene discover the body. Yakub and his thugs are killed by the cops as they open fire. Col. Vijay visits Rishi's house to confront him, but is killed in an explosion planned by Rishi. This neutralises Unit X, and Rishi and Kavya soon leave the city with new identities of Hemant and Pooja Khanna.\n\nA mid-credits scene shows Dixit buying machine guns from a local gun store in Miami before putting on a [[hoodie]] and walking away.\n\n==Cast==\n<!--As this film has Sequel been released, additions to this section must be sourced, per WP:CRYSTAL-->\n* [[Sidharth Malhotra]] as Rishi Purohit/ Gaurav Kapoor  \n* [[Jacqueline Fernandez]] as Kavya Rishi Purohit\n* [[Suniel Shetty]] as Colonel Vijay Kumar Saxena\n* [[Darshan Kumaar]] as Yakub Sabri\n* [[Hussain Dalal]] as Arth Dixit, Rishi's friend and colleague\n* [[Rajit Kapur]] as Kavya's father\n* [[Supriya Pilgaonkar]] as Kavya's mother\n* [[Amit Mistry]] as Jignesh Patel\n* [[Sijoy Varghese]] as Ramachandra Rao\n* [[Shaheed Woods]] as Koko\n* [[Kushal Punjabi]] as Willy\n* Zachary Coffin as CEO Jim\n* Hemant Koumar as Robbie\n* Nikita Sachdev as Nikki\n* [[Shahid Kapoor]] Gaurav Kapoor Plastic Before Surgery\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n\nSiddharth Anand has stated that the movie was originally envisioned as a sequel to the 2014 film [[Bang Bang!]] However, it was later clarified in an interview that the movie would be a standalone.<ref name=sequel>{{cite web | url = http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141012/entertainment-bollywood/article/bang-bang-sequel | title = Bang Bang sequel on?|website=[[Deccan Chronicle]] | date = 12 October 2014 | accessdate = 12 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/bang-bang%E2%80%99-a-sequel-in-the-pipeline_1481537.html | title = 'Bang Bang': A sequel in the pipeline? |website=Zeenews.india.com| date = 8 October 2014 | accessdate = 12 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ibtimes.co.in/hrithik-roshan-katrina-kaifs-bang-bang-have-sequel-soon-610704 | title = Hrithik Roshan, Katrina Kaif's 'Bang Bang' to have a Sequel Soon? |website=Ibtimes.co.in| date = 7 October 2014 | accessdate = 12 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming began in mid-2016 under the working title ''Reloaded''.<ref name=\"bb2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/sidharth-malhotra-gets-injured-on-reloaded-sets-4428364/ |title=Sidharth Malhotra gets injured on Reload sets |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date=2016-12-15 |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref> In September 2016, it was reported that the international shooting schedule of ''A Gentleman: Sundar, Susheel, Risky'' had been canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-international-shooting-schedule-of-bang-bang-reloaded-scrapped-2254978 |title=International shooting schedule of 'Bang Bang Reloaded' scrapped &#124; Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis |website=Dnaindia.com |date=2016-09-14 |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref> Later it was revealed by a close source that \"...there will be another long schedule in December but the location is yet to be finalised. It could be in Europe.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/sidharth-malhotra-and-jacqueline-fernandezs-reloaded-to-be-shot-in-thailand-now-15509.html |title=Sidharth Malhotra and Jacqueline Fernandez\u00e2\u20ac\u2122s Reloaded to be shot in Thailand now |website=Filmfare.com |date=2016-09-09 |accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/a-gentleman-first-look-sidharth-malhotra-jacqueline-fernandez-starrer-will-pique-your-interest/articleshow/59001956.cms |title=A Gentleman's first look out now.|website=timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2017-06-05 |accessdate=2017-06-06}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Gentleman: Sundar, Susheel, Risky\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 17 August 2017\n| recorded   = 2016\u20132017\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack|Feature film Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 16:15\n| language   = [[Hindi]]\n| label      = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Bhoomi (film)|Bhoomi]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = [[Hindi Medium]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc = {{External media\n| audio1      = {{YouTube|U_OAyJNQ3-A|Official Audio Jukebox}}\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = A Gentleman\n | type        = Soundtrack\n | single1     = Disco Disco\n | single1date = 20 July 2017\n | single2     = Baat Ban Jaye\n | single2date = 27 July 2017\n | single3     = Chandalekha\n | single3date = 4 August 2017\n | single4     = Bandook Meri Laila\n | single4date = 16 August 2017\n}}\n}}\nThe music of the film is composed by [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]] while the lyrics have been penned by Vayu and [[Priya Saraiya]]. Its first song titled as \"Disco Disco\" sung by [[Benny Dayal]] and [[Shirley Setia]] was released on 17 July 2017.  The second song to be released was \"Bandook Meri Laila\" which is sung by [[Ash King]] and [[Jigar Saraiya]] and rapped by [[Raftaar (rapper)|Raftaar]] and [[Sidharth Malhotra]] was released on 24 July 2017. The song marks Malhotra's singing debut. It was the most popular song on the album. The third song \"Baat Ban Jaye\" sung by [[Siddharth Basrur]] and [[Priya Saraiya]] was released on 5 August 2017. The fourth song was a romantic one \"Laagi Na Choote which was also a chartbuster after Bandook Meri Laila. It was released on 13 August 2017.The last but not the least song titled as \"Chandralekha\" which is sung by [[Vishal Dadlani]] and [[Jonita Gandhi]] was released on 24 August 2017. The soundtrack which includes five songs was released on 24 August 2017 by [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]].\n{{tracklist\n| headline =Track listing \n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length=16:15\n| title1 = Disco Disco\n| extra1 = [[Benny Dayal]], [[Shirley Setia]]\n| lyrics1 = Vayu\n| all_music = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| length1 = 2:47\n| title2 = Baat Ban Jaye\n| extra2 = [[Siddharth Basrur]], [[Priya Saraiya]]\n| lyrics2 = [[Priya Saraiya]]\n| length2 = 3:12\n| title3 = Chandralekha\n| extra3 = [[Vishal Dadlani]], [[Jonita Gandhi]]\n| lyrics3 = Vayu\n| length3 = 3:12\n| title4 = Laagi Na Choote\n| lyrics4 = Priya Saraiya\n| extra4 = [[Arijit Singh]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]]\n| length4 = 3:30\n| title5 = Bandook Meri Laila\n| length5 = 3:34\n| extra5 = [[Ash King]], [[Jigar Saraiya]] Rap: [[Raftaar (rapper)|Raftaar]], [[Sidharth Malhotra]]\n| lyrics5 = Vayu\n}}\n\n== Critical Reception ==\n\n===Domestic===\n[[Times of India]] rated the film 3.5 stars out of 5 and concluded, \"The film would have been a perfect entertainer had it held its cards closer to its chest. However, it still has plenty bang for your buck.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/a-gentleman/movie-review/60219419.cms\n |title=A Gentleman Movie Review |accessdate=2017-08-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Hindustan Times]] gave the film 3 out of 5, saying, \"A Gentleman is not a flawless film but Raj and DK have managed to narrate the  story in their own quirky style and their dialogues and the screenplay make it fun to watch.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/a-gentleman-movie-review-sidharth-malhotra-jacqueline-film-is-sundar-but-is-it-susheel/story-kQSSECk7BfVEUtzHw7xWFL.html |title=A Gentleman movie review: Sidharth Malhotra takes you on a risky ride, but it's worth it |accessdate=2017-08-25}}</ref>\n\n===UAE===\nThe movie released on 24 August in Dubai, UAE. Dollz in Dubai gave it 3.5 out of 5 stars calling it a masala entertainer and wrote \"It\u2019s a big step for Siddharth Malhotra who manages to carry the film and commands the screen with his presence. Yes, he\u2019s good looking but he pulls off the action sequences really well.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dollzindubai.com/2017/08/25/movie-review-a-gentleman-sundar-susheel-risky/|title=Movie Review: A Gentleman \u2013 Sundar, Susheel, Risky|last=+Ekta|date=2017-08-24|website=Dollz in Dubai|access-date=2017-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5613834|A Gentleman}}\n*[https://www.facebook.com/AGentlemanTheMovie/ A Gentleman Official]  at [[Facebook]]\n* [http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/a-gentleman/ A Gentleman] at [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gentleman, A}}\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s action adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s spy comedy films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian action comedy films]]\n[[Category:Indian action adventure films]]\n[[Category:Indian spy comedy films]]\n[[Category:Indian adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:Fox Star Studios films]]\n[[Category:Masala films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Gentleman"}
{"title_page": "Basil Gribbin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2014}}\n'''Basil Gribbin''' was a co-ordinating magistrate in the [[Beenleigh]] [[Magistrates' Court of Queensland|Magistrates Court]] and a member of the Queensland Magistrates Association, which is the equivalent of a Magistrates Union.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/8.30/lawrpt/stories/s1401264.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604182857/http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/8.30/lawrpt/stories/s1401264.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 June 2011 |title=Di Fingleton; The Siege of Glenrowan |date=28 June 2005 |access-date=30 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Gribbin served as a Magistrate from 9 January 1987 to 10 May 2008.<ref name=\"Annual Report 2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.courts.qld.gov.au/MagistratesCourt/M-AR-2007-08-Part2.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003222006/http://www.courts.qld.gov.au/MagistratesCourt/M-AR-2007-08-Part2.pdf |archive-date=3 October 2009 |url-status=dead |title=Annual Report 2008 |publisher=Magistrates Court of Queensland}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nGribbin commenced his working life as a clerk at the Magistrates Court at [[Warwick, Queensland|Warwick]] in 1964. He later worked as a registrar in over nine court registries including [[Springsure]], [[Herberton]], [[Cairns]], [[Beenleigh]], [[Inala, Queensland|Inala]] and [[Rockhampton, Queensland|Rockhampton]]. After being admitted as a legal practitioner in late 1984, he undertook a series of appointments as Acting Magistrate at Herberton, Cairns, Beenleigh, Inala and Rockhampton over a two-year period before being appointed as a Queensland Magistrate.<ref name=\"Annual Report 2008\"/>\n\nIn 1998, Queensland Courts established a Rules Committee to introduce and monitor the Uniform Civil Procedure Rules. Magistrate Gribbin served as one of the court's two representatives on the committee since its inception \u2013 a role he relinquished just prior to his retirement.<ref name=\"Annual Report 2008\"/>\n\n==Role in imprisonment of Di Fingleton==\nHe is most famous for having written an [[affidavit]] in 2002 in support of a fellow magistrate named Ann Thacker, who was challenging a decision made by then [[Chief Magistrate]], [[Di Fingleton]] to transfer her from [[Brisbane]] to [[Townsville]].<ref name=\"ABC\"/> This resulted in Fingleton sending Gribbin an email asking him to show cause why she should not dismiss him from the position of supervising magistrate. Gribbin responded by accusing her of attempting to pervert the course of justice and trying to interfere with his right to give evidence in support of Thacker.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> Gribbin referred the matter to the [[Department of Public Prosecutions]] (DPP), and this resulted in Fingleton being convicted of the offence of retaliating against a [[witness]]. Her conviction was later quashed on appeal in a unanimous decision of the [[High Court of Australia]].<ref name=\"Fingleton HCA\">{{cite AustLII|HCA|34|2005|litigants=Fingleton v R |parallelcite=(2005) 227 [[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]] 166 |courtname=auto |date=23 June 2005}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gribbin, Basil}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian magistrates]]\n[[Category:People from Queensland]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2014}}\n'''Basil Gribbin''' was a co-ordinating magistrate in the [[Beenleigh]] [[Magistrates' Court of Queensland|Magistrates Court]] and a member of the Queensland Magistrates Association, which is the equivalent of a Magistrates Union.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/8.30/lawrpt/stories/s1401264.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604182857/http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/8.30/lawrpt/stories/s1401264.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 June 2011 |title=Di Fingleton; The Siege of Glenrowan |date=28 June 2005 |access-date=30 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Gribbin served as a Magistrate from 9 January 1987 to 10 May 2008.<ref name=\"Annual Report 2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.courts.qld.gov.au/MagistratesCourt/M-AR-2007-08-Part2.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003222006/http://www.courts.qld.gov.au/MagistratesCourt/M-AR-2007-08-Part2.pdf |archive-date=3 October 2009 |url-status=dead |title=Annual Report 2008 |publisher=Magistrates Court of Queensland}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nGribbin commenced his working life as a clerk at the Magistrates Court at [[Warwick]] in 1964. He later worked as a registrar in over nine court registries including [[Springsure]], [[Herberton]], [[Cairns]], [[Beenleigh]], [[Inala, Queensland|Inala]] and [[Rockhampton, Queensland|Rockhampton]]. After being admitted as a legal practitioner in late 1984, he undertook a series of appointments as Acting Magistrate at Herberton, Cairns, Beenleigh, Inala and Rockhampton over a two-year period before being appointed as a Queensland Magistrate.<ref name=\"Annual Report 2008\"/>\n\nIn 1998, Queensland Courts established a Rules Committee to introduce and monitor the Uniform Civil Procedure Rules. Magistrate Gribbin served as one of the court\u2019s two representatives on the committee since its inception \u2013 a role he relinquished just prior to his retirement.<ref name=\"Annual Report 2008\"/>\n\n==Role in imprisonment of Di Fingleton==\nHe is most famous for having written an [[affidavit]] in 2002 in support of a fellow magistrate named Ann Thacker, who was challenging a decision made by then [[Chief Magistrate]], [[Di Fingleton]] to transfer her from [[Brisbane]] to [[Townsville]].<ref name=\"ABC\"/> This resulted in Fingleton sending Gribbin an email asking him to show cause why she should not dismiss him from the position of supervising magistrate. Gribbin responded by accusing her of attempting to pervert the course of justice and trying to interfere with his right to give evidence in support of Thacker.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> Gribbin referred the matter to the [[Department of Public Prosecutions]] (DPP), and this resulted in Fingleton being convicted of the offence of retaliating against a [[witness]]. Her conviction was later quashed on appeal in a unanimous decision of the [[High Court of Australia]].<ref name=\"Fingleton HCA\">{{cite AustLII|HCA|34|2005|litigants=Fingleton v R |parallelcite=(2005) 227 [[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]] 166 |courtname=auto |date=23 June 2005}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gribbin, Basil}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian magistrates]]\n[[Category:People from Queensland]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegal career:Fix placename links, replaced:Warwick\u2192Warwick,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basil_Gribbin"}
{"title_page": "Prince Paul of Yugoslavia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = Paul\n| title        = [[Prince Regent]]\n| image        = Prince Paul of Yugoslavia.jpg\n| caption      = Prince Paul of Yugoslavia in 1935\n| succession   = [[List of Yugoslav regents|Prince Regent of Yugoslavia]]\n| reign        = {{nowrap|9 October 1934 \u2013 27 March 1941}}\n| reign-type   = Tenure\n| reg-type     = [[List of heads of state of Yugoslavia|Monarch]]\n| regent       = [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter II]]\n| spouse       = [[Princess Olga of Greece and Denmark]]\n| issue        = [[Prince Alexander of Yugoslavia (1924\u20132016)|Prince Alexander]]<br/>[[Prince Nikola of Yugoslavia (1928\u20131954)|Prince Nicholas]]<br/>[[Princess Elizabeth of Yugoslavia|Princess Elizabeth]]\n| full name    = Pavle Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107\n| house = [[House of Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107|Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107]]\n| father       = [[Prince Arsen of Yugoslavia]]\n| mother       = [[Aurora Pavlovna Demidova]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1893|4|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1976|9|14|1893|4|27|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| burial_date  =\n| burial_place = [[Oplenac|St. George's Church]], [[Serbia]]\n| religion     = [[Serbian Orthodox]]\n| module      = {{Infobox military person | embed=yes\n  | allegiance    = {{flag|Kingdom of Serbia}}<br>{{flag|Kingdom of Yugoslavia}}\n  | branch        = \n  | serviceyears  = 1911\u20131935 (active service)\n  | rank          = [[Army General]]\n  | servicenumber = \n  | unit          = [[Cavalry]]\n  | commands      = \n  | battles_label = \n  | battles       = \n  | awards        =\n  }}\n}}\n{{Infobox royal styles\n| name     = Prince Paul of Yugoslavia\n| image    = [[File:Royal Monogram of Prince Paul Yugoslavia.svg|50px]]\n| dipstyle = [[Royal Highness|His Royal Highness]]\n| offstyle = Your Royal Highness\n| altstyle = Sir\n}}\n'''Prince Paul of Yugoslavia''', also known as '''Paul Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107''' ({{lang-sh|Pavle Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107}}, \u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0452\u043e\u0440\u0452\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b, English transliteration: ''Paul Karageorgevich''; 27 April 1893 \u2013 14 September 1976), was [[Prince Regent]] of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] during the minority of [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|King Peter II]]. Paul was a first cousin of Peter's father [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|Alexander I]].\n\n==Early life==\nPrince Paul of Yugoslavia was the only son of [[Arsen Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107, Prince of Serbia|Prince Arsen of Serbia]], younger brother of [[Peter I of Serbia|King Peter I]], and of Princess and Countess [[Aurora Pavlovna Demidova|Aurora Pavlovna Demidova di San Donato]], a granddaughter on one side of the [[Finland|Finnish]] philanthropist [[Aurora Karamzin]] and her Russian husband Prince and Count [[Pavel Nikolaievich Demidov]] and on the other of the Russian Prince [[Peter Troubetzkoy]] and his wife [[Elizabeth Trubetskaya|Elisabeth Esperovna]], by birth a Princess [[Belosselsky-Belozersky family|Belosselsky-Belozersky]].\n\nPaul was educated at [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], where he was a member of the exclusive [[Bullingdon Club]] \u2013 a dining club notorious for its wealthy members, grand banquets and boisterous rituals. Cultivated<ref>Bradford, Sarah ''Elizabeth: A Biography of Britain's Queen'', Riverhead Books 1997, p. 46</ref> like his closest friends [[Prince George, Duke of Kent]], and [[Henry Channon|Sir Henry Channon]],<ref>Channon, Paul ''Chips: The Diaries of Sir Henry Channon'', Weidenfeld & Nicolson, 1967, p. 192</ref> his outlook on life was said to be [[United Kingdom|British]]. Paul often said that he \"felt like an Englishman\".{{sfn|Keegan|1989|p=151}} Channon called Paul \"the person I have loved most\".<ref>{{cite web\n |last        = Williams \n |first       = Emma \n |coauthors   = \n |title       = A Royal Quest\n |work        = \n |publisher   = 1843\n |date        = March\u2013April 2013\n |url         = https://www.1843magazine.com/content/ideas/emma-williams/princess-elizabeth-yugoslavia\n |doi         = \n |accessdate  = 2019-02-01\n |df          = \n}}</ref> A cultured and easy-going bon vivant who inspired much affection from his friends, Paul when not associating with the British aristocracy collected paintings by Monet, Titian and van Gogh.<ref>{{cite web\n |last        = Williams \n |first       = Emma \n |coauthors   = \n |title       = A Royal Quest\n |work        = \n |publisher   = 1843\n |date        = March\u2013April 2013\n |url         = https://www.1843magazine.com/content/ideas/emma-williams/princess-elizabeth-yugoslavia\n |doi         = \n |accessdate  = 2019-02-01\n |df          = \n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923 he married [[Princess Olga of Greece and Denmark]], a sister of [[Princess Marina, Duchess of Kent]]. [[George VI of the United Kingdom|King George VI]], when [[Duke of York]], was best man at his wedding in [[Belgrade]].<ref>{{cite web\n |last        = Williams \n |first       = Emma \n |coauthors   = \n |title       = A Royal Quest\n |work        = \n |publisher   = 1843\n |date        = March\u2013April 2013\n |url         = https://www.1843magazine.com/content/ideas/emma-williams/princess-elizabeth-yugoslavia\n |doi         = \n |accessdate  = 2019-02-01\n |df          = \n}}</ref>\n\n==Regent of Yugoslavia==\n[[File:Royal Standard of the Prince Regent of Yugoslavia (1937\u20131941).svg|thumb|left|180px|Standard of the Prince Regent]]\nOn 9 October 1934 [[Vlado Chernozemski]] assassinated Paul's first-cousin, [[King Alexander I of Yugoslavia]], in [[Marseille]] in [[French Third Republic|France]], and Prince Paul took the [[regency]], as Alexander had stipulated in his Will that on his death a council of regents chaired by Paul should govern until Alexander's son [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter II]] came of age.<ref>Hoptner, J.B, {{cite web| url = https://archive.org/stream/yugoslaviaincris012757mbp/yugoslaviaincris012757mbp_djvu.txt| title = ''Yugoslavia in crisis 1934\u20131941''}}, Columbia University Press, 1962, p. 25</ref>\n\nPrince Paul, far more than Alexander, was [[Yugoslavism|Yugoslav rather than Serb]] in outlook, and unlike Alexander, he was inclined much more toward democracy. In its broadest outline, his domestic policy worked to eliminate the heritage of the [[6 January Dictatorship|Alexandrine dictatorship's]] centralism, censorship, and military control, and to pacify the country by solving the Serb-Croat problem.<ref>Hoptner, p. 26</ref> Paul wanted to achieve a Serb-Croat reconciliation, but also felt for a considerable period of time that he had the duty to hand over the kingdom to Peter more or less unchanged when he reached his maturity, and thus was unwilling to entertain constitutional changes.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=139}} Through as Prince Regent, Paul possessed very broad powers, but he was much less inclined to exercise these powers, leading Yugoslavia in the years 1934-41 to be labelled \"a dictatorship without a dictator\".{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=139}} Paul had been thrust into a position of power that he did not want by Alexander's assassination (which was why Alexander had chosen him in his will to serve as a regent, knowing he would never try to seize the throne from his son), and throughout his regency he gave the impression that ruling Yugoslavia was a burden to him.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=139}} A French diplomat described Paul as a man whose \"incontestable qualities of character, balance, and taste...Oxonian dilettantism and charm which he exercised on his visitors where were useless in the present circumstances and in a country where arguments of might are the only ones which count\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=202}} Married to a [[Kingdom of Greece|Greek]] princess and intensely [[Anglophile]] and [[Hellenophile]], Paul distrusted [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|Fascist Italy]] and [[Nazi Germany]], though the British historian D. C. Watt noted that Paul's \"nerves tended to betray him under stress and that he was by nature inclined to yield to pressure rather than withstand it\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=202}} The heavy losses taken by [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbia]] in [[World War I]] made Paul very averse to engaging in another war and led him to favoring neutralist policies despite Yugoslavia's alliance with France.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=290}} During the First World War, Serbia had proportionally taken the [[World War I casualties|heaviest losses]]; one out of five Serbs who were alive in 1914 were dead by 1918.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=131}}\n\nOn 24 June 1935, Paul appointed [[Milan Stojadinovi\u0107]] Prime Minister with a mandate to deal with the Great Depression and find a solution to the \"Croat question\".{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=140}} Stojadinovi\u0107 believed that the solution to the Great Depression were closer economic ties with Germany, which had more people than what it could feed and lacked many of the raw materials necessary for a modern industrial economy.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=140}} As Germany needed both food and raw materials such as iron, bauxite, copper and manganese, Yugoslav exports of both agricultural products and of minerals to the ''Reich'' bloomed from 1935 onward, leading to an economic revival and to placing Yugoslavia in the German economic sphere of influence.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=140}}\n\nYugoslavia had signed a treaty of alliance with France in 1927, at a time when the [[Rhineland]] was still [[Occupation of the Rhineland|occupied by France]], and during Franco-Yugoslav staff talks, it was promised that France would take the offensive into western Germany if Germany should start another war. As long as the Rhineland remained a demilitarized zone, there was always the possibility of the French launching an offensive into western Germany, which reassured Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Weinberg|1970|p=239-240 & 261}} The American historian Gerhard Weinberg wrote that the demilitarized status of the Rhineland the treaty of Versailles had imposed was \"...the single most important guarantee of peace in Europe\" for as long as the Rhineland was demilitarized, it was impossible for Germany to attack any of France's allies in Eastern Europe without exposing itself to the risk of a devastating French offensive into western Germany.{{sfn|Weinberg|1970|p=239-240}} The [[remilitarization of the Rhineland]] on 7 March 1936 meant that Germany started building the West Wall along its border with France, which ended any hope of a French offensive into western Germany. On 15\u201320 June 1936, the chiefs of staff of the [[Little Entente]] ([[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]], [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]] and Yugoslavia) met in [[Bucharest]] to discuss their plans now that the Rhineland was re-militarized.{{sfn|Weinberg|1970|p=261}} The gloomy conclusion of the Bucharest meeting was that France was not a factor in Eastern Europe, and henceforward there were only two great powers in Eastern Europe, namely the [[Soviet Union]] and Germany, and the victory of either in another war would mean the end of their independence.{{sfn|Weinberg|1970|p=261}}\n\nDespite his pro-British and pro-French feelings, Paul believed in the aftermath of the remilitarization of the Rhineland that Yugoslavia needed to tilt its foreign policy towards Germany.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=216}} Likewise, the [[Hoare\u2013Laval Pact|Hoare-Laval pact]] of 1935 and British attempts to improve Anglo-Italian relations such as the [[Nyon Conference|\"Gentlemen's Agreement\" of 1937]] and the [[Easter Accords]] of 1938 caused Paul to believe the British were willing to sacrifice Yugoslavia for the sake of better relations with Italy.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=216}} Stojadinovi\u0107, who openly admired Fascist Italy and Nazi Germany, made a major diplomatic push with the tacit support of the Prince Regent for better relations with the fascist states in the winter of 1936-37.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=216-217}} Without informing France, Czechoslovakia or Romania, Stojadinovi\u0107 signed an agreement with Italy on 25 March 1937 that badly weakened the Little Entente.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=217}} Just before Stojadinovi\u0107 signed the treaty, Paul let the British minister in [[Belgrade]], [[Ronald Hugh Campbell|Ronald Campbell]], know of what was being planned.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=217}} Paul seems to have believed that if Yugoslavia was seen as failing within the Italian sphere of influence, then this might prompt a British response to pull Yugoslavia in the other direction.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=217}} \n[[File:MIguelBenesCarolIIPabloDeYugoslavia1936.jpeg|thumb|King [[Carol II of Romania]] with Czechoslovak President [[Edvard Bene\u0161]], Yugoslav regent Prince Paul, and [[Prince Nicholas of Romania]] in Bucharest in 1936.|alt=]]\nIn January 1939, Stojadinovi\u0107 had told Count [[Galeazzo Ciano]] of his wish to turn his [[Yugoslav Radical Union]] into the only legal party, saying he wanted to establish a fascist dictatorship that carry out a pro-Italian foreign policy \"to find a balanced situation and security within the framework of the [[Axis powers|Axis]]\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} At the same time, the Croat deputies in the ''skupshtina'' (parliament) called on foreign powers to intervene to give the Croats \"liberty of choice and destiny\", accusing Stojadinovi\u0107 of being a tyrant.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} On 4 February 1939, Paul dismissed Stojadinovi\u0107 as prime minister and at that point the Yugoslav tilt towards the Axis was stopped.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} After dismissing Stojadinovi\u0107, Paul rejected an Italian appeal to support the Italian annexation of [[Albanian Kingdom (1928\u20131939)|Albania]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=207}} On 15 March 1939, [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia|Germany occupied]] the Czech half of the rump state of [[Second Czechoslovak Republic|Czecho-Slovakia]] (as Czechoslovakia had been renamed in October 1938), turning it into the [[Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]].{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=590}} The fact that despite the way that [[Emil H\u00e1cha]] and the rest of the leaders of Czecho-Slovakia had endeavored to carry out a slavishly pro-German foreign policy, nonetheless saw the ''Reich'' extinguish its independence came as a considerable shock to Paul.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=590}}\n\nLater, when the [[Italian invasion of Albania|Italians did annex Albania]] on Easter weekend 1939, Paul declined to make a protest, which severely strained relations with Yugoslavia's [[Balkan Pact]] ally [[Turkey]], which protested most vehemently against the annexation of a Muslim majority nation which the Turks had historically close ties with.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} The Italian annexation of Albania led to Italy controlling both sides of the [[Strait of Otranto]], and thus allowed the Italians to cut Yugoslavia off from access to the rest of the world.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=590}} On 12 May 1939, Britain and Turkey issued a joint declaration promising \"to ensure the establishment of security in the [[Balkans]]\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=291}} As Paul was about to make a state visit to Italy, he found the statement from the Turkish ambassador in Belgrade suggesting that Yugoslavia work with Turkey in the spirit of the Anglo-Turkish declaration to resist any further Italian advances in the Balkans very poorly timed and made it clear that he wanted nothing to do with the Turkish proposal.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=291}}\n\nHowever, Paul did back a plan floated by the Turkish foreign minister [[\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Saraco\u011flu]] for [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]] to join the Balkan Pact, and in a letter urged [[King Carol II of Romania]] to cede part of the [[Dobruja]] region as the price of Bulgaria joining the Balkan Pact.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=292}} In his letter, Paul stressed the importance of stopping Italy from gobbling up more Balkan nations, which required getting the Bulgarians out of the Italian sphere of influence ([[King Boris III of Bulgaria]] was married to the daughter of King [[Victor Emmanuel III of Italy]]).{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=292}} He wrote that he wanted the Bulgarians \"off my back\" to allow the Yugoslavs and Greeks to focus on countering the Italians who were now building up their forces in their [[Italian protectorate of Albania (1939\u20131943)|new colony of Albania]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=292}} Unlike the [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920-1946)|Hungarians]], whom Paul felt would never abandon their claims against Yugoslavia, the Bulgarians were felt to be more tractable.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=282}} After Germany and Italy, Hungary was the nation that Paul worried about the most as he noted that Danube river valley ran down from the Hungarian plain straight to Belgrade.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=282}} At the same time, Yugoslavia began staff talks with Greece with the aim of resisting an Italian invasion of either nation.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=291}} A major problem for Yugoslavia was the lack of modern weapons together with the money to pay for them.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} Watt wrote that \"Paul's tactics were aimed at winning credits and securing arms deliveries wherever he could, in [[Berlin]], [[Paris]] or [[London]]\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} After talking to [[Raymond Brug\u00e8re]], the French minister in Belgrade, the latter promised the prince regent that he would fly to Paris personally to lobby for Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} On 29 June 1939, it was that announced that the Bank Seligmannn of Paris was going to make a loan of 600 million francs to Yugoslavia that was to be spent on weapons for the [[Royal Yugoslav Army|Yugoslav military]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} The Germans had broken the Yugoslav diplomatic codes and were well aware of Paul's attempts to play off the [[Axis powers]] against the [[Allies of World War II|Allied powers]] to secure the best deal for Yugoslavia; Paul's salvation in 1939 rested with the fact that Germany was about to invade [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]] and needed raw materials from Yugoslavia like bauxite and copper to keep the German armaments industry going.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} \n\nIn 1939, Prince Paul, as acting head of state, accepted an official invitation from [[Adolf Hitler]] and spent nine days in Berlin. During his visit to Berlin, a massive effort was made to persuade Paul to not join the \"peace front\" that was meant to \"contain\" Germany.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} Paul was greeted by Hitler at the train station in Berlin, was made the guest of honor at a reception and dinner at the Reich Chancellery, visited the Potsdam military base, saw a gala performance of Wagner at the Berlin opera, and reviewed two major military parades meant to impress upon him the power of the ''Reich''.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} For the first part of his trip, Paul stayed at Bellevue, an old imperial palace and then for the last three days, at Goring's estate at Karinhall.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} Despite all the pomp, Paul during his visit to Germany repeatedly refused the demands made by his hosts to sign an economic agreement that would have turned Yugoslavia into a German economic colony or some overt pro-Axis gesture like pulling Yugoslavia out of the [[League of Nations]] and signing the [[Anti-Comintern Pact]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}}{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=591}} The German foreign minister [[Joachim von Ribbentrop]] called Paul a \"log\" (a German slang term meaning somebody who is very stupid) while Hitler was very angry that despite all the lavish hospitality the only concession Paul made was to slightly readjust the exchange rate between the ''[[Reichmark]]'' and the [[Yugoslav dinar|Dinar]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} In return for readjusting the exchange rate, Paul forced the Germans to finally deliver some of the aircraft that Yugoslavia had paid for in advance in 1938, but the Germans kept finding excuses not to deliver.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}}\n\nWhile he was in Germany, Paul dispatched General [[Petar Pe\u0161i\u0107]] on a secret mission to Paris and London to find out what were the Anglo-French plans in the event of a war.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} Pe\u0161i\u0107 told [[Lord Gort]] of the British General Staff and French Marshal [[Maurice Gamelin]] that Yugoslavia would declare neutrality if Germany invaded Poland, but would be willing to enter the war on the Allied side the moment the [[Mediterranean]] and [[Adriatic sea]]s came under Allied operational control.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} Pe\u0161i\u0107 argued that from the Allied viewpoint that Yugoslav neutrality could be advantageous in the sense that Yugoslavia at present could not stop the German [[Wehrmacht]] from occupying the country if Hitler so desired, which would allow the Germans to exploit all of the crucial raw materials of Yugoslavia whereas if Yugoslavia remained neutral and entered the war when the Allies could support her, then those raw materials would be permanently denied to the Germans.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} Pe\u0161i\u0107 found that the French, who preferred that fighting take place in anywhere but France, were far more interested in having Yugoslavia enter the conflict if the [[Danzig crisis]] should lead to a war than the British.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} From Marshal Gamelin he learned the French were already planning on having the [[Army of the Levant]] commanded by [[Maxime Weygand]] land at [[Thessaloniki]] to march up the Balkans to link up with the Yugoslavs and the Romanians to aid the Poles.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} In May 1939, Yugoslavia changed its diplomatic codes, which stopped both the Italians and Germans from reading the Yugoslav codes.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} The same month, when the Romanian Foreign Minister, [[Grigore Gafencu]], visited Belgrade, Paul spoke to him of his wish for both Yugoslavia and Romania to have closer ties with Britain.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} Despite repeated pressure from both the German and Italian ministers in Belgrade, Paul refused their demand that Yugoslavia leave the League of Nations as a symbolic move to show that Yugoslavia was now associated with the Axis states.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} As Germany and [[Empire of Japan|Japan]] had both left the League of Nations in 1933 while Italy had left the League in 1937, the Axis powers always attached immense symbolic importance to having other nations leaving the League as showing diplomatic alignment with them.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=591}}\n\nIn June 1939, Paul warned the [[United States|American]] ambassador to Yugoslavia that the ''Forschungsamt'' (research office) was reading all of the diplomatic cables going into and out of Belgrade, including the American ones, and the ambassador should be careful what information he cabled back to [[Washington D.C.|Washington]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} On 15 July 1939, Paul left Belgrade to visit London with a stop over in Paris to see Pe\u0161i\u0107.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} From Pe\u0161i\u0107, Paul learned that he had the impression that on one hand, the French were keen to start a second front in the Balkans in the event of war while on the other hand that the French Navy would play only a defensive role, guarding convoys from [[French Algeria|Algeria]] to France. In London, Paul advocated that Britain launch a \"[[preemptive war]]\" against Italy, saying that if Italy were knocked out, then Yugoslavia would definitely move closer to Britain.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} Paul ordered that the Yugoslav National Bank's gold reserves be transferred to London as a sign of his faith in Britain.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} He told his British hosts that Yugoslavia was not ready to join the \"peace front\" yet, but was moving in that direction.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} Paul also told the Foreign Secretary, [[Lord Halifax]], that he would use his influence with the more hesitant Balkan Pact nations, namely Romania and Greece to try to bring them into the \"peace front\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} During the same visit, he was installed as a [[Knight of the Garter]], the most important British order of chivalry, by [[King George VI]], which greatly offended Hitler, who complained that Paul's heart was with the British.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}}\n\nDuring his talks with Lord Halifax in London, Paul received elusive replies to his demands for a British \"preemptive war\" against Italy as Paul contended that as long as the ''[[Regia Marina]]'' existed, there was always the possibility of Yugoslavia being cut off from Britain and France.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} Both the Prime Minister, [[Neville Chamberlain]], and Lord Halifax regarded Italian leader [[Benito Mussolini]] as the more moderate and reasonable of the fascist leaders who despite signing the [[Pact of Steel]] in May might still be \"peeled off\" from his alliance with Germany.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} Fearful of being cut off, Paul advocated to Halifax that if Britain ended up declaring war on Germany as a result of the latter invading Poland, then Britain should immediately launch air and naval attacks to destroy the ''Regia Marina'' and the ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]'' regardless if Italy was neutral or not.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} It was Paul's belief that even if Mussolini declared neutrality at first that it was inevitable that he would come into the war on Germany's side at some point.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} Paul very much wanted an Anglo-French landing at the Greek city of Thessaloniki in the event of war as he believed that this was the only way that Yugoslavia could resist a German invasion.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} Paul also expressed his hope that the British would include the Soviet Union the proposed \"peace front\" as the best way of deterring Germany from invading Poland.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} At the same that Paul was visiting London, the Yugoslav minister of finance [[Vojin \u0110uri\u010di\u0107]] was in Paris where he signed on 14 July an agreement with the Premier [[\u00c9douard Daladier]] for France to sell Yugloslavia anti-aircraft guns, trucks, howitzers, anti-tank guns, machine guns, tanks and tank transporters.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}}\n\nAs the Danzig crisis pushed Europe to the brink of war, [[Vladko Ma\u010dek]] of the [[Croatian Peasant Party]] became convinced of the necessity of \"throwing a bridge across the abyss which separated Serb from Croat\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} Paul supported Prime Minister [[Dragi\u0161a Cvetkovi\u0107]]'s efforts to reach an understanding with Ma\u010dek, as despite his wish to hand over Yugoslavia unchanged to King Peter when he reached his majority, he felt that an end to the Serb-Croat dispute was the best way to allow Yugoslavia to survive the coming storm.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=141-142}} On 20 August 1939, the [[Cvetkovi\u0107-Ma\u010dek Agreement]] set up the [[Banovina of Croatia]] to be ruled by a ''ban'' (governor) responsible to the king and a ''sabor'' (parliament) in [[Zagreb]].{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}} The central government retained control of the monarchy, foreign affairs, national defence, foreign trade, commerce, transport, public security, religion, mining, weights and measures, insurance, and education policy, but Croatia was to have its own legislature in [[Zagreb]], with a separate budget.<ref>Hoptner, p. 154</ref> The ''sprorazum'' (agreement) granted broad autonomy to Croatia, and partitioned [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]] and [[Herzegovina]] as the government agreed to Ma\u010dek's demand that all of the Croats in Yugoslavia should live under the authority of the Croatian ''banovina''.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}} The ''sprorazum'' was popular with moderate Croat opinion, but it was extremely unpopular with the [[Bosnian Muslims]] who objected to the partition of Bosnia-Herzegovina.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}} Likewise, the Serbian opinion was outraged by that the ''sprorazum'' had \"abandoned\" the ''[[Pre\u010dani (Serbs)|pre\u010dani]]'' Serbs in Bosnia and the ''[[Bosanska Krajina|Krajina]]'' region to Croat rule.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}} The charge that Paul and Cvetkovi\u0107 had \"sold out\" to the Croats with the ''sprorazum'' made them unpopular with the Serbs, and if it did not cause the [[Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat of 26 March 1941]], certainly was the essential prerequisite for the coup.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142-142}} Finally, the [[Slovenes]] demanded that a similar degree of autonomy should be granted to them.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}}\n\nOn 26 August 1939 as the [[Danzig crisis]] moved towards its climax, Paul in a letter to Lord Halifax once again urged that Britain launch a \"preemptive war\" against Italy if Germany should invade Poland.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} The prince regent warned if Germany conquered Poland, then Italy would sooner or later enter the war, and if that happened, the Italian forces in Albania with support from Bulgaria would be used to threaten the other Balkan states.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} Paul concluded in that case \"a rot throughout the Balkans\" would follow as the other Balkan states together with Turkey would turn towards Germany to protect them from Italy.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} Sir [[Ronald Ian Campbell|Ronald Campbell]], the British minister in Belgrade in a cable to Lord Halifax wrote that Paul was \"in the last stages of despair\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} Halifax wrote on the margin on Paul's letter that he was suffering from [[manic-depression]] again.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=473}} Brug\u00e8re, who very much liked Paul, proved more sympathetic, and in a dispatch to Paris urged that France land a force at Thessaloniki if Germany should invade Poland.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=473}} The French proved supportive of the idea of landing at Thessaloniki, but Allied strategy was determined by an Inter-Allied War Council, and the British were stoutly opposed to the French plans for a \"second front\" in the Balkans.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=473}}\n\nThe news of the [[Ribbentrop-Molotov Pact]] was an especially bitter blow for Paul as it ensured that the two strongest powers in Eastern Europe would be working together, and ended the regent's hopes of an Anglo-French alliance which might finally rid Yugoslavia of the constant Italian efforts to undermine national unity.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=473}} When the [[Second World War]] broke out in September 1939 with the [[German invasion of Poland]], Yugoslavia declared its neutrality.<ref>Hoptner, p. 167</ref> During the \"[[Phoney War]]\", Paul arranged for Yugoslavia to step up deliveries of copper to Germany in exchanges for promises that Germany would finally deliver arms that Yugoslavia had paid for in advance, but which the ''Reich'' kept finding excuses not to deliver.{{sfn|Weinberg|2004|p=78}} Germany also wanted that Yugoslavia not only refuse to join the British-inspired \"peace front\", but also formally align its diplomacy with the Axis powers.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=590}} In his sympathies, Paul preferred that France and Britain win the war, but he was markedly afraid of the Wehrmacht.{{sfn|Weinberg|2004|p=78}} Paul repeatedly pressed for a revival of the [[Salonika Front]] strategy of [[First World War]], arguing that if French and British forces landed at Thessaloniki, which would place them in a position to aid Yugoslavia, then he might lean more towards the Allied side.{{sfn|Weinberg|2004|p=78}} During the Phony War, a popular, if erroneous rumor in Croatia that Paul was planning to enter the war on the Allied side and send Croat regiments to man the [[Maginot Line]] in France increased support for Croat separatism.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}}\n\nOn 25 March 1941, the [[Yugoslav accession to the Tripartite Pact|Yugoslav government signed]] the Axis [[Tripartite Pact]], with significant reservations, as three notes were appended. The first note obliged the Axis powers to respect the territorial integrity and sovereignty of Yugoslavia. In the second note the Axis powers promised not to ask Yugoslavia for any military assistance, and in the third they promised not to ask permission to move military forces across Yugoslav territory during the war.<ref>Hoptner, p. 240</ref> Nonetheless, the signing of the pact did not sit well with several elements of the [[Royal Yugoslav Army]]. On 27 March 1941, two days after Yugoslavia had signed the Tripartite Pact, Yugoslav military figures with British support [[Yugoslav coup of 1941|forcibly removed Paul from power]] and declared King Peter II of age.<ref>Hoptner, p. 266</ref> German and Italian forces [[Invasion of Yugoslavia|invaded the country]] ten days later.\n\n==Exile==\n[[File:Coat of arms of Prince Paul of Yugoslavia.png|thumb|upright|Paul's coat of arms]]\nFor the remainder of the war, Prince Paul was kept, with his family, under [[house arrest]] by the British in [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]]. His sister-in-law the [[Princess Marina, Duchess of Kent|Duchess of Kent]] and her husband the [[Prince George, Duke of Kent|Duke]], appealed to [[Winston Churchill]], hoping he would allow Paul and his wife, [[Princess Olga of Greece and Denmark|Princess Olga]], to take refuge in Britain. However, Churchill rejected the request in no uncertain manner; he viewed Paul as a traitor and war criminal. After the Duke of Kent's death in 1942, Churchill relented to King George's insistence and allowed Olga to fly to London to comfort her sister\u2013although without her husband, who had been extremely close to the late Duke.<ref>{{Cite journal| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-princess-paul-of-yugoslavia-1291926.html| title=Obituary: Princess Paul of Yugoslavia|journal=The Independent|date=1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Aronson |first=Theo |date=2014 |title=The Royal Family at War |location= |publisher=Thistle Publishing |pages=204, 205}}</ref>\n\nThe post-war [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Communist authorities in Yugoslavia]] had Prince Paul proclaimed an enemy of the state, barred him from ever returning to Yugoslavia, and confiscated all of his property in Yugoslavia. He died in Paris on 14 September 1976, aged 83<ref>''The Times'', Thursday, 16 September 1976, p. 16</ref> and was buried at the [[Bois-de-Vaux Cemetery]] in [[Switzerland]].\n\n[[Princess Elizabeth of Yugoslavia|Princess Elizabeth]], his only daughter, obtained information from the British [[Special Operations Executive]] files in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] in London and published them in Belgrade, in the 1990 edition of the Serbian-language biography of her father. The original book ''Paul of Yugoslavia: Britain's Maligned Friend'' was written by Neil Balfour, the first was published by Eaglet Publishing in London in 1980.\n\nPrince Paul was rehabilitated by the Serbian courts in 2011 and on 6 October 2012 was reburied at the family crypt of [[Oplenac]], near [[Topola]] in central Serbia, together with his wife Olga and son [[Prince Nikola of Yugoslavia (1928\u20131954)|Nikola]].<ref>[http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/serbia-to-repatriate-its-royal-family Balkaninsight]</ref>\n\nPrince Paul was the father of [[Princess Elizabeth of Yugoslavia|Princess Elizabeth]], [[Prince Alexander of Yugoslavia the Elder|Prince Alexander]], and [[Prince Nikola of Yugoslavia (1928\u20131954)|Prince Nikola]], and was the grandfather of the American author [[Christina Oxenberg]] and American actress [[Catherine Oxenberg]].\n\n==Art collections==\nPrince Paul, together with [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|King Alexander I of Yugoslavia]] collected, donated and dedicated a large number of art works to Serbia and the Serbian people, including foreign masterpieces. There are especially significant Italian, French and Dutch/Flemish pieces. Most of the works are in the [[National Museum of Serbia]], including work by artists such as [[Peter Paul Rubens|Rubens]], [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir|Renoir]], [[Claude Monet|Monet]], [[Titian]], [[Vincent van Gogh|Van Gogh]], [[Paul Gauguin]] etc.\n\n==Honours==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Serbian and Yugoslavian decorations'''\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order of the Kara\u0111or\u0111e's Star rib.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Kara\u0111or\u0111e's Star]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=SRB Orden Belog Orla BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the White Eagle (Serbia)|Order of the White Eagle]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Ordre_de_la_Couronne_de_Yougoslavie_(Royaume).png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Yugoslav Crown]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Ord.St.Sava-ribbon.jpg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of St. Sava]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Serbian Service Medals'''\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Conmemorative Medal of the Accesion of King Peter I.jpg|width=60}}\n| Commemorative Medal of the Election of Peter I as King of Serbia\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Commemorative_Medal_of_the_Albanian_Campaign,1920_rib.png|width=60}}\n|[[Albanian Commemorative Medal|Commemorative Medal of the Albanian Campaign]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Red Cross Medal of Merit rib.gif|width=60}}\n|Medal of the Serbian [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]]\n|-\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Foreign Honours'''\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=OrderofCarolI.ribbon.gif|width=60}}\n|[[Order of Carol I]], Grand Collar \n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=UK_Royal_Victorian_Order_ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Royal Victorian Order]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order_of_the_Garter_UK_ribbon.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Garter]], Knight\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order_of_St_John_(UK)_ribbon.png|width=60}}\n|[[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Sovereign Military Order of Malta]], Bailiff Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Orderelefant_ribbon.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Elephant]], Knight\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Legion Honneur GC ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Honour]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=GRE_Order_Redeemer_1Class.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Redeemer]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=GRE_Order_of_George_I_-_Grand_Cross_BAR.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of George I]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order of the Most Holy Annunciation BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Supreme Order of the Most Holy Annunciation]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Cavaliere_di_gran_Croce_Regno_SSML_BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Cavaliere_di_Gran_Croce_OCI_Kingdom_BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Crown of Italy]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order of the Golden Fleece ribbon bar.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Golden Fleece]], Knight Grand Cross<ref>{{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Acovi\u0107|first=Dragomir|title=Slava i \u010dast: Odlikovanja me\u0111u Srbima, Srbi me\u0111u odlikovanjima|year=2012|location=Belgrade|publisher=Slu\u017ebeni Glasnik|pages=332}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|1= 1. '''Paul, Prince Regent of Yugoslavia'''\n|2= 2. [[Prince Arsen of Yugoslavia]]\n|3= 3. [[Aurora Pavlovna Demidova|Princess Aurora Pavlovna Demidova]]\n|4= 4. [[Alexander Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107, Prince of Serbia]]\n|5= 5. [[Persida Nenadovi\u0107]]\n|6= 6. [[Pavel Pavlovich Demidov, 2nd Prince of San Donato]]\n|7= 7. Princess Elena Petrovna [[:File:Trubetskoy_Coat_of_Arms.png|Trubetskaya]]\n|8= 8. [[Kara\u0111or\u0111e Petrovi\u0107]]\n|9= 9. [[:\u0414\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0430:Jelena_petrovic.jpg|Jelena Jovanovi\u0107]]\n|10= 10. [[Obor-knez|Voivode]] [[Jevrem Nenadovi\u0107]]\n|11= 11. Jovanka [[Mladen Milovanovi\u0107|Milovanovi\u0107]]\n|12= 12. [[Pavel Nikolaievich Demidov|Count Pavel Nikolaievich Demidov]]\n|13= 13. [[Aurora Karamzin|Aurora Stjernvall]]\n|14= 14. Prince Pyotr Nikitich [[Trubetskoy family|Trubetskoy]]\n|15= 15. Princess Elizaveta Esperovna [[Belosselsky-Belozersky family|Belosselska-Belozerska]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Crampton, Richard ''Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century-And After'', London: Routledge, 1997. \n*Keegan, John ''The Second World War'', New York: Viking, 1989.\n*Watt, D. C. ''How War Came The Immediate Origins of the Second World War, 1938\u201339'', London: Heinemannm, 1989''.\n*Weinberg, Gerhard ''The Foreign Policy of Hitler's Germany Starting World War II'', Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1980.\n*Weinberg, Gerhard ''A World At Arms A Global History of World War II'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2004.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Prince Paul of Yugoslavia}}\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/013302}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107]]|27 April|1893|14 September|1976}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-vac|last   = [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|Alexander]]|as=[[Regent|Regent of Serbia]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title  = [[List of Yugoslav regents|Regent of Yugoslavia]]|years = 9 October 1934 \u2013 27 March 1941}}\n{{S-vac|reason = [[Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat]] and declared [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter II]] of age}}\n{{S-mil|}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{Succession box |\n |before=''Position established''\n |title=Deputy [[List of heads of state of Yugoslavia|Commander in Chief]] of the [[Royal Yugoslav Army|Yugoslavian Armed Forces]]\n|years= 1935\u20131941\n |after=[[Petar Bojovi\u0107]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Yugoslav Head of State}}\n{{Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107 dynasty}}\n{{Serbian princes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paul Of Yugoslavia}}\n[[Category:Yugoslav princes]]\n[[Category:Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107 dynasty]]\n[[Category:Regents]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Victorian Chain]]\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Leaders ousted by a coup]]\n[[Category:World War II political leaders]]\n[[Category:Serbian art collectors]]\n[[Category:Serbian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Serbian people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Finnish descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Mausoleum of the Royal House of Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107, Oplenac]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Yugoslav Crown]]\n[[Category:Serbian exiles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = Paul\n| title        = [[Prince Regent]]\n| image        = Prince Paul of Yugoslavia.jpg\n| caption      = Prince Paul of Yugoslavia in 1935\n| succession   = [[List of Yugoslav regents|Prince Regent of Yugoslavia]]\n| reign        = {{nowrap|9 October 1934 \u2013 27 March 1941}}\n| reign-type   = Tenure\n| reg-type     = [[List of heads of state of Yugoslavia|Monarch]]\n| regent       = [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter II]]\n| spouse       = [[Princess Olga of Greece and Denmark]]\n| issue        = [[Prince Alexander of Yugoslavia (1924\u20132016)|Prince Alexander]]<br/>[[Prince Nikola of Yugoslavia (1928\u20131954)|Prince Nicholas]]<br/>[[Princess Elizabeth of Yugoslavia|Princess Elizabeth]]\n| full name    = Pavle Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107\n| house = [[House of Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107|Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107]]\n| father       = [[Prince Arsen of Yugoslavia]]\n| mother       = [[Aurora Pavlovna Demidova]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1893|4|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1976|9|14|1893|4|27|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| burial_date  =\n| burial_place = [[Oplenac|St. George's Church]], [[Serbia]]\n| religion     = [[Serbian Orthodox]]\n| module      = {{Infobox military person | embed=yes\n  | allegiance    = {{flag|Kingdom of Serbia}}<br>{{flag|Kingdom of Yugoslavia}}\n  | branch        = \n  | serviceyears  = 1911\u20131935 (active service)\n  | rank          = [[Army General]]\n  | servicenumber = \n  | unit          = [[Cavalry]]\n  | commands      = \n  | battles_label = \n  | battles       = \n  | awards        =\n  }}\n}}\n{{Infobox royal styles\n| name     = Prince Paul of Yugoslavia\n| image    = [[File:Royal Monogram of Prince Paul Yugoslavia.svg|50px]]\n| dipstyle = [[Royal Highness|His Royal Highness]]\n| offstyle = Your Royal Highness\n| altstyle = Sir\n}}\n'''Prince Paul of Yugoslavia''', also known as '''Paul Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107''' ({{lang-sh|Pavle Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107}}, \u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0452\u043e\u0440\u0452\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b, English transliteration: ''Paul Karageorgevich''; 27 April 1893 \u2013 14 September 1976), was [[Prince Regent]] of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] during the minority of [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|King Peter II]]. Paul was a first cousin of Peter's father [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|Alexander I]].\n\n==Early life==\nPrince Paul of Yugoslavia was the only son of [[Arsen Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107, Prince of Serbia|Prince Arsen of Serbia]], younger brother of [[Peter I of Serbia|King Peter I]], and of Princess and Countess [[Aurora Pavlovna Demidova]], a granddaughter on one side of the [[Finland|Finnish]] philanthropist [[Aurora Karamzin]] and her Russian husband Prince and Count [[Pavel Nikolaievich Demidov]] and on the other of the Russian Prince [[Peter Troubetzkoy]] and his wife [[Elizabeth Trubetskaya|Elisabeth Esperovna]], by birth a Princess [[Belosselsky-Belozersky family|Belosselsky-Belozersky]].\n\nPaul was educated at [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], where he was a member of the exclusive [[Bullingdon Club]] \u2013 a dining club notorious for its wealthy members, grand banquets and boisterous rituals. Cultivated<ref>Bradford, Sarah ''Elizabeth: A Biography of Britain's Queen'', Riverhead Books 1997, p. 46</ref> like his closest friends [[Prince George, Duke of Kent]], and [[Henry Channon|Sir Henry Channon]],<ref>Channon, Paul ''Chips: The Diaries of Sir Henry Channon'', Weidenfeld & Nicolson, 1967, p. 192</ref> his outlook on life was said to be [[United Kingdom|British]]. Paul often said that he \"felt like an Englishman\".{{sfn|Keegan|1989|p=151}} Channon called Paul \"the person I have loved most\".<ref>{{cite web\n |last        = Williams \n |first       = Emma \n |coauthors   = \n |title       = A Royal Quest\n |work        = \n |publisher   = 1843\n |date        = March\u2013April 2013\n |url         = https://www.1843magazine.com/content/ideas/emma-williams/princess-elizabeth-yugoslavia\n |doi         = \n |accessdate  = 2019-02-01\n |df          = \n}}</ref> A cultured and easy-going bon vivant who inspired much affection from his friends, Paul when not associating with the British aristocracy collected paintings by Monet, Titian and van Gogh.<ref>{{cite web\n |last        = Williams \n |first       = Emma \n |coauthors   = \n |title       = A Royal Quest\n |work        = \n |publisher   = 1843\n |date        = March\u2013April 2013\n |url         = https://www.1843magazine.com/content/ideas/emma-williams/princess-elizabeth-yugoslavia\n |doi         = \n |accessdate  = 2019-02-01\n |df          = \n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923 he married [[Princess Olga of Greece and Denmark]], a sister of [[Princess Marina, Duchess of Kent]]. [[George VI of the United Kingdom|King George VI]], when [[Duke of York]], was best man at his wedding in [[Belgrade]].<ref>{{cite web\n |last        = Williams \n |first       = Emma \n |coauthors   = \n |title       = A Royal Quest\n |work        = \n |publisher   = 1843\n |date        = March\u2013April 2013\n |url         = https://www.1843magazine.com/content/ideas/emma-williams/princess-elizabeth-yugoslavia\n |doi         = \n |accessdate  = 2019-02-01\n |df          = \n}}</ref>\n\n==Regent of Yugoslavia==\n[[File:Royal Standard of the Prince Regent of Yugoslavia (1937\u20131941).svg|thumb|left|180px|Standard of the Prince Regent]]\nOn 9 October 1934 [[Vlado Chernozemski]] assassinated Paul's first-cousin, [[King Alexander I of Yugoslavia]], in [[Marseille]] in [[French Third Republic|France]], and Prince Paul took the [[regency]], as Alexander had stipulated in his Will that on his death a council of regents chaired by Paul should govern until Alexander's son [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter II]] came of age.<ref>Hoptner, J.B, {{cite web| url = https://archive.org/stream/yugoslaviaincris012757mbp/yugoslaviaincris012757mbp_djvu.txt| title = ''Yugoslavia in crisis 1934\u20131941''}}, Columbia University Press, 1962, p. 25</ref>\n\nPrince Paul, far more than Alexander, was [[Yugoslavism|Yugoslav rather than Serb]] in outlook, and unlike Alexander, he was inclined much more toward democracy. In its broadest outline, his domestic policy worked to eliminate the heritage of the [[6 January Dictatorship|Alexandrine dictatorship's]] centralism, censorship, and military control, and to pacify the country by solving the Serb-Croat problem.<ref>Hoptner, p. 26</ref> Paul wanted to achieve a Serb-Croat reconciliation, but also felt for a considerable period of time that he had the duty to hand over the kingdom to Peter more or less unchanged when he reached his maturity, and thus was unwilling to entertain constitutional changes.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=139}} Through as Prince Regent, Paul possessed very broad powers, but he was much less inclined to exercise these powers, leading Yugoslavia in the years 1934-41 to be labelled \"a dictatorship without a dictator\".{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=139}} Paul had been thrust into a position of power that he did not want by Alexander's assassination (which was why Alexander had chosen him in his will to serve as a regent, knowing he would never try to seize the throne from his son), and throughout his regency he gave the impression that ruling Yugoslavia was a burden to him.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=139}} A French diplomat described Paul as a man whose \"incontestable qualities of character, balance, and taste...Oxonian dilettantism and charm which he exercised on his visitors where were useless in the present circumstances and in a country where arguments of might are the only ones which count\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=202}} Married to a [[Kingdom of Greece|Greek]] princess and intensely [[Anglophile]] and [[Hellenophile]], Paul distrusted [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|Fascist Italy]] and [[Nazi Germany]], though the British historian D. C. Watt noted that Paul's \"nerves tended to betray him under stress and that he was by nature inclined to yield to pressure rather than withstand it\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=202}} The heavy losses taken by [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbia]] in [[World War I]] made Paul very averse to engaging in another war and led him to favoring neutralist policies despite Yugoslavia's alliance with France.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=290}} During the First World War, Serbia had proportionally taken the [[World War I casualties|heaviest losses]]; one out of five Serbs who were alive in 1914 were dead by 1918.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=131}}\n\nOn 24 June 1935, Paul appointed [[Milan Stojadinovi\u0107]] Prime Minister with a mandate to deal with the Great Depression and find a solution to the \"Croat question\".{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=140}} Stojadinovi\u0107 believed that the solution to the Great Depression were closer economic ties with Germany, which had more people than what it could feed and lacked many of the raw materials necessary for a modern industrial economy.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=140}} As Germany needed both food and raw materials such as iron, bauxite, copper and manganese, Yugoslav exports of both agricultural products and of minerals to the ''Reich'' bloomed from 1935 onward, leading to an economic revival and to placing Yugoslavia in the German economic sphere of influence.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=140}}\n\nYugoslavia had signed a treaty of alliance with France in 1927, at a time when the [[Rhineland]] was still [[Occupation of the Rhineland|occupied by France]], and during Franco-Yugoslav staff talks, it was promised that France would take the offensive into western Germany if Germany should start another war. As long as the Rhineland remained a demilitarized zone, there was always the possibility of the French launching an offensive into western Germany, which reassured Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Weinberg|1970|p=239-240 & 261}} The American historian Gerhard Weinberg wrote that the demilitarized status of the Rhineland the treaty of Versailles had imposed was \"...the single most important guarantee of peace in Europe\" for as long as the Rhineland was demilitarized, it was impossible for Germany to attack any of France's allies in Eastern Europe without exposing itself to the risk of a devastating French offensive into western Germany.{{sfn|Weinberg|1970|p=239-240}} The [[remilitarization of the Rhineland]] on 7 March 1936 meant that Germany started building the West Wall along its border with France, which ended any hope of a French offensive into western Germany. On 15\u201320 June 1936, the chiefs of staff of the [[Little Entente]] ([[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]], [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]] and Yugoslavia) met in [[Bucharest]] to discuss their plans now that the Rhineland was re-militarized.{{sfn|Weinberg|1970|p=261}} The gloomy conclusion of the Bucharest meeting was that France was not a factor in Eastern Europe, and henceforward there were only two great powers in Eastern Europe, namely the [[Soviet Union]] and Germany, and the victory of either in another war would mean the end of their independence.{{sfn|Weinberg|1970|p=261}}\n\nDespite his pro-British and pro-French feelings, Paul believed in the aftermath of the remilitarization of the Rhineland that Yugoslavia needed to tilt its foreign policy towards Germany.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=216}} Likewise, the [[Hoare\u2013Laval Pact|Hoare-Laval pact]] of 1935 and British attempts to improve Anglo-Italian relations such as the [[Nyon Conference|\"Gentlemen's Agreement\" of 1937]] and the [[Easter Accords]] of 1938 caused Paul to believe the British were willing to sacrifice Yugoslavia for the sake of better relations with Italy.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=216}} Stojadinovi\u0107, who openly admired Fascist Italy and Nazi Germany, made a major diplomatic push with the tacit support of the Prince Regent for better relations with the fascist states in the winter of 1936-37.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=216-217}} Without informing France, Czechoslovakia or Romania, Stojadinovi\u0107 signed an agreement with Italy on 25 March 1937 that badly weakened the Little Entente.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=217}} Just before Stojadinovi\u0107 signed the treaty, Paul let the British minister in [[Belgrade]], [[Ronald Hugh Campbell|Ronald Campbell]], know of what was being planned.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=217}} Paul seems to have believed that if Yugoslavia was seen as failing within the Italian sphere of influence, then this might prompt a British response to pull Yugoslavia in the other direction.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=217}} \n[[File:MIguelBenesCarolIIPabloDeYugoslavia1936.jpeg|thumb|King [[Carol II of Romania]] with Czechoslovak President [[Edvard Bene\u0161]], Yugoslav regent Prince Paul, and [[Prince Nicholas of Romania]] in Bucharest in 1936.|alt=]]\nIn January 1939, Stojadinovi\u0107 had told Count [[Galeazzo Ciano]] of his wish to turn his [[Yugoslav Radical Union]] into the only legal party, saying he wanted to establish a fascist dictatorship that carry out a pro-Italian foreign policy \"to find a balanced situation and security within the framework of the [[Axis powers|Axis]]\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} At the same time, the Croat deputies in the ''skupshtina'' (parliament) called on foreign powers to intervene to give the Croats \"liberty of choice and destiny\", accusing Stojadinovi\u0107 of being a tyrant.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} On 4 February 1939, Paul dismissed Stojadinovi\u0107 as prime minister and at that point the Yugoslav tilt towards the Axis was stopped.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} After dismissing Stojadinovi\u0107, Paul rejected an Italian appeal to support the Italian annexation of [[Albanian Kingdom (1928\u20131939)|Albania]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=207}} On 15 March 1939, [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia|Germany occupied]] the Czech half of the rump state of [[Second Czechoslovak Republic|Czecho-Slovakia]] (as Czechoslovakia had been renamed in October 1938), turning it into the [[Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]].{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=590}} The fact that despite the way that [[Emil H\u00e1cha]] and the rest of the leaders of Czecho-Slovakia had endeavored to carry out a slavishly pro-German foreign policy, nonetheless saw the ''Reich'' extinguish its independence came as a considerable shock to Paul.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=590}}\n\nLater, when the [[Italian invasion of Albania|Italians did annex Albania]] on Easter weekend 1939, Paul declined to make a protest, which severely strained relations with Yugoslavia's [[Balkan Pact]] ally [[Turkey]], which protested most vehemently against the annexation of a Muslim majority nation which the Turks had historically close ties with.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} The Italian annexation of Albania led to Italy controlling both sides of the [[Strait of Otranto]], and thus allowed the Italians to cut Yugoslavia off from access to the rest of the world.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=590}} On 12 May 1939, Britain and Turkey issued a joint declaration promising \"to ensure the establishment of security in the [[Balkans]]\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=291}} As Paul was about to make a state visit to Italy, he found the statement from the Turkish ambassador in Belgrade suggesting that Yugoslavia work with Turkey in the spirit of the Anglo-Turkish declaration to resist any further Italian advances in the Balkans very poorly timed and made it clear that he wanted nothing to do with the Turkish proposal.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=291}}\n\nHowever, Paul did back a plan floated by the Turkish foreign minister [[\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Saraco\u011flu]] for [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]] to join the Balkan Pact, and in a letter urged [[King Carol II of Romania]] to cede part of the [[Dobruja]] region as the price of Bulgaria joining the Balkan Pact.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=292}} In his letter, Paul stressed the importance of stopping Italy from gobbling up more Balkan nations, which required getting the Bulgarians out of the Italian sphere of influence ([[King Boris III of Bulgaria]] was married to the daughter of King [[Victor Emmanuel III of Italy]]).{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=292}} He wrote that he wanted the Bulgarians \"off my back\" to allow the Yugoslavs and Greeks to focus on countering the Italians who were now building up their forces in their [[Italian protectorate of Albania (1939\u20131943)|new colony of Albania]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=292}} Unlike the [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920-1946)|Hungarians]], whom Paul felt would never abandon their claims against Yugoslavia, the Bulgarians were felt to be more tractable.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=282}} After Germany and Italy, Hungary was the nation that Paul worried about the most as he noted that Danube river valley ran down from the Hungarian plain straight to Belgrade.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=282}} At the same time, Yugoslavia began staff talks with Greece with the aim of resisting an Italian invasion of either nation.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=291}} A major problem for Yugoslavia was the lack of modern weapons together with the money to pay for them.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} Watt wrote that \"Paul's tactics were aimed at winning credits and securing arms deliveries wherever he could, in [[Berlin]], [[Paris]] or [[London]]\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} After talking to [[Raymond Brug\u00e8re]], the French minister in Belgrade, the latter promised the prince regent that he would fly to Paris personally to lobby for Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} On 29 June 1939, it was that announced that the Bank Seligmannn of Paris was going to make a loan of 600 million francs to Yugoslavia that was to be spent on weapons for the [[Royal Yugoslav Army|Yugoslav military]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} The Germans had broken the Yugoslav diplomatic codes and were well aware of Paul's attempts to play off the [[Axis powers]] against the [[Allies of World War II|Allied powers]] to secure the best deal for Yugoslavia; Paul's salvation in 1939 rested with the fact that Germany was about to invade [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]] and needed raw materials from Yugoslavia like bauxite and copper to keep the German armaments industry going.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} \n\nIn 1939, Prince Paul, as acting head of state, accepted an official invitation from [[Adolf Hitler]] and spent nine days in Berlin. During his visit to Berlin, a massive effort was made to persuade Paul to not join the \"peace front\" that was meant to \"contain\" Germany.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} Paul was greeted by Hitler at the train station in Berlin, was made the guest of honor at a reception and dinner at the Reich Chancellery, visited the Potsdam military base, saw a gala performance of Wagner at the Berlin opera, and reviewed two major military parades meant to impress upon him the power of the ''Reich''.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} For the first part of his trip, Paul stayed at Bellevue, an old imperial palace and then for the last three days, at Goring's estate at Karinhall.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} Despite all the pomp, Paul during his visit to Germany repeatedly refused the demands made by his hosts to sign an economic agreement that would have turned Yugoslavia into a German economic colony or some overt pro-Axis gesture like pulling Yugoslavia out of the [[League of Nations]] and signing the [[Anti-Comintern Pact]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}}{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=591}} The German foreign minister [[Joachim von Ribbentrop]] called Paul a \"log\" (a German slang term meaning somebody who is very stupid) while Hitler was very angry that despite all the lavish hospitality the only concession Paul made was to slightly readjust the exchange rate between the ''[[Reichmark]]'' and the [[Yugoslav dinar|Dinar]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}} In return for readjusting the exchange rate, Paul forced the Germans to finally deliver some of the aircraft that Yugoslavia had paid for in advance in 1938, but the Germans kept finding excuses not to deliver.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=293}}\n\nWhile he was in Germany, Paul dispatched General [[Petar Pe\u0161i\u0107]] on a secret mission to Paris and London to find out what were the Anglo-French plans in the event of a war.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} Pe\u0161i\u0107 told [[Lord Gort]] of the British General Staff and French Marshal [[Maurice Gamelin]] that Yugoslavia would declare neutrality if Germany invaded Poland, but would be willing to enter the war on the Allied side the moment the [[Mediterranean]] and [[Adriatic sea]]s came under Allied operational control.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} Pe\u0161i\u0107 argued that from the Allied viewpoint that Yugoslav neutrality could be advantageous in the sense that Yugoslavia at present could not stop the German [[Wehrmacht]] from occupying the country if Hitler so desired, which would allow the Germans to exploit all of the crucial raw materials of Yugoslavia whereas if Yugoslavia remained neutral and entered the war when the Allies could support her, then those raw materials would be permanently denied to the Germans.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} Pe\u0161i\u0107 found that the French, who preferred that fighting take place in anywhere but France, were far more interested in having Yugoslavia enter the conflict if the [[Danzig crisis]] should lead to a war than the British.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} From Marshal Gamelin he learned the French were already planning on having the [[Army of the Levant]] commanded by [[Maxime Weygand]] land at [[Thessaloniki]] to march up the Balkans to link up with the Yugoslavs and the Romanians to aid the Poles.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}} In May 1939, Yugoslavia changed its diplomatic codes, which stopped both the Italians and Germans from reading the Yugoslav codes.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} The same month, when the Romanian Foreign Minister, [[Grigore Gafencu]], visited Belgrade, Paul spoke to him of his wish for both Yugoslavia and Romania to have closer ties with Britain.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} Despite repeated pressure from both the German and Italian ministers in Belgrade, Paul refused their demand that Yugoslavia leave the League of Nations as a symbolic move to show that Yugoslavia was now associated with the Axis states.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} As Germany and [[Empire of Japan|Japan]] had both left the League of Nations in 1933 while Italy had left the League in 1937, the Axis powers always attached immense symbolic importance to having other nations leaving the League as showing diplomatic alignment with them.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=591}}\n\nIn June 1939, Paul warned the [[United States|American]] ambassador to Yugoslavia that the ''Forschungsamt'' (research office) was reading all of the diplomatic cables going into and out of Belgrade, including the American ones, and the ambassador should be careful what information he cabled back to [[Washington D.C.|Washington]].{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} On 15 July 1939, Paul left Belgrade to visit London with a stop over in Paris to see Pe\u0161i\u0107.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} From Pe\u0161i\u0107, Paul learned that he had the impression that on one hand, the French were keen to start a second front in the Balkans in the event of war while on the other hand that the French Navy would play only a defensive role, guarding convoys from [[French Algeria|Algeria]] to France. In London, Paul advocated that Britain launch a \"[[preemptive war]]\" against Italy, saying that if Italy were knocked out, then Yugoslavia would definitely move closer to Britain.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} Paul ordered that the Yugoslav National Bank's gold reserves be transferred to London as a sign of his faith in Britain.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} He told his British hosts that Yugoslavia was not ready to join the \"peace front\" yet, but was moving in that direction.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} Paul also told the Foreign Secretary, [[Lord Halifax]], that he would use his influence with the more hesitant Balkan Pact nations, namely Romania and Greece to try to bring them into the \"peace front\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}} During the same visit, he was installed as a [[Knight of the Garter]], the most important British order of chivalry, by [[King George VI]], which greatly offended Hitler, who complained that Paul's heart was with the British.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=295}}\n\nDuring his talks with Lord Halifax in London, Paul received elusive replies to his demands for a British \"preemptive war\" against Italy as Paul contended that as long as the ''[[Regia Marina]]'' existed, there was always the possibility of Yugoslavia being cut off from Britain and France.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} Both the Prime Minister, [[Neville Chamberlain]], and Lord Halifax regarded Italian leader [[Benito Mussolini]] as the more moderate and reasonable of the fascist leaders who despite signing the [[Pact of Steel]] in May might still be \"peeled off\" from his alliance with Germany.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} Fearful of being cut off, Paul advocated to Halifax that if Britain ended up declaring war on Germany as a result of the latter invading Poland, then Britain should immediately launch air and naval attacks to destroy the ''Regia Marina'' and the ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]'' regardless if Italy was neutral or not.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} It was Paul's belief that even if Mussolini declared neutrality at first that it was inevitable that he would come into the war on Germany's side at some point.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} Paul very much wanted an Anglo-French landing at the Greek city of Thessaloniki in the event of war as he believed that this was the only way that Yugoslavia could resist a German invasion.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} Paul also expressed his hope that the British would include the Soviet Union the proposed \"peace front\" as the best way of deterring Germany from invading Poland.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=296}} At the same that Paul was visiting London, the Yugoslav minister of finance [[Vojin \u0110uri\u010di\u0107]] was in Paris where he signed on 14 July an agreement with the Premier [[\u00c9douard Daladier]] for France to sell Yugloslavia anti-aircraft guns, trucks, howitzers, anti-tank guns, machine guns, tanks and tank transporters.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=294}}\n\nAs the Danzig crisis pushed Europe to the brink of war, [[Vladko Ma\u010dek]] of the [[Croatian Peasant Party]] became convinced of the necessity of \"throwing a bridge across the abyss which separated Serb from Croat\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=203}} Paul supported Prime Minister [[Dragi\u0161a Cvetkovi\u0107]]'s efforts to reach an understanding with Ma\u010dek, as despite his wish to hand over Yugoslavia unchanged to King Peter when he reached his majority, he felt that an end to the Serb-Croat dispute was the best way to allow Yugoslavia to survive the coming storm.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=141-142}} On 20 August 1939, the [[Cvetkovi\u0107-Ma\u010dek Agreement]] set up the [[Banovina of Croatia]] to be ruled by a ''ban'' (governor) responsible to the king and a ''sabor'' (parliament) in [[Zagreb]].{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}} The central government retained control of the monarchy, foreign affairs, national defence, foreign trade, commerce, transport, public security, religion, mining, weights and measures, insurance, and education policy, but Croatia was to have its own legislature in [[Zagreb]], with a separate budget.<ref>Hoptner, p. 154</ref> The ''sprorazum'' (agreement) granted broad autonomy to Croatia, and partitioned [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]] and [[Herzegovina]] as the government agreed to Ma\u010dek's demand that all of the Croats in Yugoslavia should live under the authority of the Croatian ''banovina''.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}} The ''sprorazum'' was popular with moderate Croat opinion, but it was extremely unpopular with the [[Bosnian Muslims]] who objected to the partition of Bosnia-Herzegovina.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}} Likewise, the Serbian opinion was outraged by that the ''sprorazum'' had \"abandoned\" the ''[[Pre\u010dani (Serbs)|pre\u010dani]]'' Serbs in Bosnia and the ''[[Bosanska Krajina|Krajina]]'' region to Croat rule.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}} The charge that Paul and Cvetkovi\u0107 had \"sold out\" to the Croats with the ''sprorazum'' made them unpopular with the Serbs, and if it did not cause the [[Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat of 26 March 1941]], certainly was the essential prerequisite for the coup.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142-142}} Finally, the [[Slovenes]] demanded that a similar degree of autonomy should be granted to them.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}}\n\nOn 26 August 1939 as the [[Danzig crisis]] moved towards its climax, Paul in a letter to Lord Halifax once again urged that Britain launch a \"preemptive war\" against Italy if Germany should invade Poland.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} The prince regent warned if Germany conquered Poland, then Italy would sooner or later enter the war, and if that happened, the Italian forces in Albania with support from Bulgaria would be used to threaten the other Balkan states.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} Paul concluded in that case \"a rot throughout the Balkans\" would follow as the other Balkan states together with Turkey would turn towards Germany to protect them from Italy.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} Sir [[Ronald Ian Campbell|Ronald Campbell]], the British minister in Belgrade in a cable to Lord Halifax wrote that Paul was \"in the last stages of despair\".{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=472}} Halifax wrote on the margin on Paul's letter that he was suffering from [[manic-depression]] again.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=473}} Brug\u00e8re, who very much liked Paul, proved more sympathetic, and in a dispatch to Paris urged that France land a force at Thessaloniki if Germany should invade Poland.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=473}} The French proved supportive of the idea of landing at Thessaloniki, but Allied strategy was determined by an Inter-Allied War Council, and the British were stoutly opposed to the French plans for a \"second front\" in the Balkans.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=473}}\n\nThe news of the [[Ribbentrop-Molotov Pact]] was an especially bitter blow for Paul as it ensured that the two strongest powers in Eastern Europe would be working together, and ended the regent's hopes of an Anglo-French alliance which might finally rid Yugoslavia of the constant Italian efforts to undermine national unity.{{sfn|Watt|1989|p=473}} When the [[Second World War]] broke out in September 1939 with the [[German invasion of Poland]], Yugoslavia declared its neutrality.<ref>Hoptner, p. 167</ref> During the \"[[Phoney War]]\", Paul arranged for Yugoslavia to step up deliveries of copper to Germany in exchanges for promises that Germany would finally deliver arms that Yugoslavia had paid for in advance, but which the ''Reich'' kept finding excuses not to deliver.{{sfn|Weinberg|2004|p=78}} Germany also wanted that Yugoslavia not only refuse to join the British-inspired \"peace front\", but also formally align its diplomacy with the Axis powers.{{sfn|Weinberg|1980|p=590}} In his sympathies, Paul preferred that France and Britain win the war, but he was markedly afraid of the Wehrmacht.{{sfn|Weinberg|2004|p=78}} Paul repeatedly pressed for a revival of the [[Salonika Front]] strategy of [[First World War]], arguing that if French and British forces landed at Thessaloniki, which would place them in a position to aid Yugoslavia, then he might lean more towards the Allied side.{{sfn|Weinberg|2004|p=78}} During the Phony War, a popular, if erroneous rumor in Croatia that Paul was planning to enter the war on the Allied side and send Croat regiments to man the [[Maginot Line]] in France increased support for Croat separatism.{{sfn|Crampton|1997|p=142}}\n\nOn 25 March 1941, the [[Yugoslav accession to the Tripartite Pact|Yugoslav government signed]] the Axis [[Tripartite Pact]], with significant reservations, as three notes were appended. The first note obliged the Axis powers to respect the territorial integrity and sovereignty of Yugoslavia. In the second note the Axis powers promised not to ask Yugoslavia for any military assistance, and in the third they promised not to ask permission to move military forces across Yugoslav territory during the war.<ref>Hoptner, p. 240</ref> Nonetheless, the signing of the pact did not sit well with several elements of the [[Royal Yugoslav Army]]. On 27 March 1941, two days after Yugoslavia had signed the Tripartite Pact, Yugoslav military figures with British support [[Yugoslav coup of 1941|forcibly removed Paul from power]] and declared King Peter II of age.<ref>Hoptner, p. 266</ref> German and Italian forces [[Invasion of Yugoslavia|invaded the country]] ten days later.\n\n==Exile==\n[[File:Coat of arms of Prince Paul of Yugoslavia.png|thumb|upright|Paul's coat of arms]]\nFor the remainder of the war, Prince Paul was kept, with his family, under [[house arrest]] by the British in [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]]. His sister-in-law the [[Princess Marina, Duchess of Kent|Duchess of Kent]] and her husband the [[Prince George, Duke of Kent|Duke]], appealed to [[Winston Churchill]], hoping he would allow Paul and his wife, [[Princess Olga of Greece and Denmark|Princess Olga]], to take refuge in Britain. However, Churchill rejected the request in no uncertain manner; he viewed Paul as a traitor and war criminal. After the Duke of Kent's death in 1942, Churchill relented to King George's insistence and allowed Olga to fly to London to comfort her sister\u2013although without her husband, who had been extremely close to the late Duke.<ref>{{Cite journal| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-princess-paul-of-yugoslavia-1291926.html| title=Obituary: Princess Paul of Yugoslavia|journal=The Independent|date=1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Aronson |first=Theo |date=2014 |title=The Royal Family at War |location= |publisher=Thistle Publishing |pages=204, 205}}</ref>\n\nThe post-war [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Communist authorities in Yugoslavia]] had Prince Paul proclaimed an enemy of the state, barred him from ever returning to Yugoslavia, and confiscated all of his property in Yugoslavia. He died in Paris on 14 September 1976, aged 83<ref>''The Times'', Thursday, 16 September 1976, p. 16</ref> and was buried at the [[Bois-de-Vaux Cemetery]] in [[Switzerland]].\n\n[[Princess Elizabeth of Yugoslavia|Princess Elizabeth]], his only daughter, obtained information from the British [[Special Operations Executive]] files in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] in London and published them in Belgrade, in the 1990 edition of the Serbian-language biography of her father. The original book ''Paul of Yugoslavia: Britain's Maligned Friend'' was written by Neil Balfour, the first was published by Eaglet Publishing in London in 1980.\n\nPrince Paul was rehabilitated by the Serbian courts in 2011 and on 6 October 2012 was reburied at the family crypt of [[Oplenac]], near [[Topola]] in central Serbia, together with his wife Olga and son [[Prince Nikola of Yugoslavia (1928\u20131954)|Nikola]].<ref>[http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/serbia-to-repatriate-its-royal-family Balkaninsight]</ref>\n\nPrince Paul was the father of [[Princess Elizabeth of Yugoslavia|Princess Elizabeth]], [[Prince Alexander of Yugoslavia the Elder|Prince Alexander]], and [[Prince Nikola of Yugoslavia (1928\u20131954)|Prince Nikola]], and was the grandfather of the American author [[Christina Oxenberg]] and American actress [[Catherine Oxenberg]].\n\n==Art collections==\nPrince Paul, together with [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|King Alexander I of Yugoslavia]] collected, donated and dedicated a large number of art works to Serbia and the Serbian people, including foreign masterpieces. There are especially significant Italian, French and Dutch/Flemish pieces. Most of the works are in the [[National Museum of Serbia]], including work by artists such as [[Peter Paul Rubens|Rubens]], [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir|Renoir]], [[Claude Monet|Monet]], [[Titian]], [[Vincent van Gogh|Van Gogh]], [[Paul Gauguin]] etc.\n\n==Honours==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Serbian and Yugoslavian decorations'''\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order of the Kara\u0111or\u0111e's Star rib.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Kara\u0111or\u0111e's Star]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=SRB Orden Belog Orla BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the White Eagle (Serbia)|Order of the White Eagle]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Ordre_de_la_Couronne_de_Yougoslavie_(Royaume).png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Yugoslav Crown]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Ord.St.Sava-ribbon.jpg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of St. Sava]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Serbian Service Medals'''\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Conmemorative Medal of the Accesion of King Peter I.jpg|width=60}}\n| Commemorative Medal of the Election of Peter I as King of Serbia\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Commemorative_Medal_of_the_Albanian_Campaign,1920_rib.png|width=60}}\n|[[Albanian Commemorative Medal|Commemorative Medal of the Albanian Campaign]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Red Cross Medal of Merit rib.gif|width=60}}\n|Medal of the Serbian [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]]\n|-\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Foreign Honours'''\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=OrderofCarolI.ribbon.gif|width=60}}\n|[[Order of Carol I]], Grand Collar \n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=UK_Royal_Victorian_Order_ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Royal Victorian Order]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order_of_the_Garter_UK_ribbon.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Garter]], Knight\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order_of_St_John_(UK)_ribbon.png|width=60}}\n|[[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Sovereign Military Order of Malta]], Bailiff Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Orderelefant_ribbon.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Elephant]], Knight\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Legion Honneur GC ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Honour]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=GRE_Order_Redeemer_1Class.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Redeemer]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=GRE_Order_of_George_I_-_Grand_Cross_BAR.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of George I]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order of the Most Holy Annunciation BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Supreme Order of the Most Holy Annunciation]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Cavaliere_di_gran_Croce_Regno_SSML_BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Cavaliere_di_Gran_Croce_OCI_Kingdom_BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Crown of Italy]], Knight Grand Cross\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|ribbon=Order of the Golden Fleece ribbon bar.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Order of the Golden Fleece]], Knight Grand Cross<ref>{{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Acovi\u0107|first=Dragomir|title=Slava i \u010dast: Odlikovanja me\u0111u Srbima, Srbi me\u0111u odlikovanjima|year=2012|location=Belgrade|publisher=Slu\u017ebeni Glasnik|pages=332}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|1= 1. '''Paul, Prince Regent of Yugoslavia'''\n|2= 2. [[Prince Arsen of Yugoslavia]]\n|3= 3. [[Aurora Pavlovna Demidova|Princess Aurora Pavlovna Demidova]]\n|4= 4. [[Alexander Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107, Prince of Serbia]]\n|5= 5. [[Persida Nenadovi\u0107]]\n|6= 6. [[Pavel Pavlovich Demidov, 2nd Prince of San Donato]]\n|7= 7. Princess Elena Petrovna Trubetskaya\n|8= 8. [[Kara\u0111or\u0111e Petrovi\u0107]]\n|9= 9. Jelena Jovanovi\u0107\n|10= 10. [[Jevrem Nenadovi\u0107]]\n|11= 11. Jovanka Milovanovi\u0107\n|12= 12. [[Pavel Nikolaievich Demidov|Count Pavel Nikolaievich Demidov]]\n|13= 13. [[Aurora Karamzin|Aurora Stjernvall]]\n|14= 14. Prince Pyotr Nikitich Trubetskoy\n|15= 15. Princess Elizaveta Esperovna Belossel'ska-Belozerska\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Crampton, Richard ''Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century-And After'', London: Routledge, 1997. \n*Keegan, John ''The Second World War'', New York: Viking, 1989.\n*Watt, D. C. ''How War Came The Immediate Origins of the Second World War, 1938\u201339'', London: Heinemannm, 1989''.\n*Weinberg, Gerhard ''The Foreign Policy of Hitler's Germany Starting World War II'', Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1980.\n*Weinberg, Gerhard ''A World At Arms A Global History of World War II'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2004.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Prince Paul of Yugoslavia}}\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/013302}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107]]|27 April|1893|14 September|1976}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-vac|last   = [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|Alexander]]|as=[[Regent|Regent of Serbia]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title  = [[List of Yugoslav regents|Regent of Yugoslavia]]|years = 9 October 1934 \u2013 27 March 1941}}\n{{S-vac|reason = [[Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat]] and declared [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter II]] of age}}\n{{S-mil|}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{Succession box |\n |before=''Position established''\n |title=Deputy [[List of heads of state of Yugoslavia|Commander in Chief]] of the [[Royal Yugoslav Army|Yugoslavian Armed Forces]]\n|years= 1935\u20131941\n |after=[[Petar Bojovi\u0107]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Yugoslav Head of State}}\n{{Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107 dynasty}}\n{{Serbian princes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paul Of Yugoslavia}}\n[[Category:Yugoslav princes]]\n[[Category:Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107 dynasty]]\n[[Category:Regents]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Victorian Chain]]\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Leaders ousted by a coup]]\n[[Category:World War II political leaders]]\n[[Category:Serbian art collectors]]\n[[Category:Serbian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Serbian people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Finnish descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Mausoleum of the Royal House of Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107, Oplenac]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Yugoslav Crown]]\n[[Category:Serbian exiles]]\n", "name_user": "93.87.163.221", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAncestry)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prince_Paul_of_Yugoslavia"}
{"title_page": "Adam Becker", "text_new": "\n\n<!--**********************************************************************\n    *  Please use template {{R|\"ref name\"}} when citing references, and  *\n    *     insert reference code within {{Reflist|30em|refs= . . . }}     *\n    *                 template under references heading.                 *\n    **********************************************************************-->\n{{short description|American astrophysicist, author and science educator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Adam Becker\n|image             = \n|image_size        = \n|caption           = \n|birth_date        = 1984\n|birth_place       = New Jersey\n|death_date        =\n|death_place       =\n|residence         = Oakland, California\n|citizenship       = United States\n|nationality       = American\n|fields            = \n|workplaces        = \n|alma_mater        = Cornell (BA: Philosophy, Physics), University of Michigan (MS: Physics, PhD: Physics) \n|thesis_title      = Is the Universe Normal? Constraining Scale-Dependent Primordial Non-Gaussianity.\n|thesis_url        = https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/handle/2027.42/93893\n|thesis_year       = 2012\n|doctoral_advisor  = Dragan Huterer\n|academic_advisors =\n|doctoral_students = \n|notable_students  =\n|known_for         = Science Communication, History of Physics, ''What is Real'' (2018)\n|influences        = \n|influenced        =\n|awards            = \n|spouse            = \n|signature         =  \n|website           = {{URL|http://freelanceastrophysicist.com}}\n| module           = \n| filename = \n| title = \n| type = \n| description = \n}}\n\n'''Adam Becker''' (born 1984) is an American astrophysicist and popularizer of science. He is a visiting scholar at [[University of California, Berkeley]].{{R|\"Basic Books\"}} His book ''What Is Real?'' explores the history and personalities of the foundations of [[quantum physics]] and reassesses the prominence of the views often grouped together as the [[Copenhagen interpretation|Copenhagen Interpretation]].\n\n== Life ==\nBorn in New Jersey in 1984, Becker received his BA in philosophy and physics from [[Cornell]] in 2006, a MS in Physics from [[University of Michigan]] in 2007 and a PhD in Physics from [[University of Michigan]] with Dragen Huterer as his [[doctoral advisor]] in 2012. His thesis was on [[Non-Gaussianity|primordial non-Gaussianity]], which he summarized in popular terms as, \"I was trying to find out how much we can learn about the way stuff was arranged in the early universe by looking at the way stuff is arranged in the universe right now.\"{{R|\"Freelance\"}}\n\nBecker worked at ''New Scientist'' magazine, and he was a researcher in the Labs division of the [[Public Library of Science]] (PLOS). {{As of|2018}}, he was a visiting scholar at the Office for History of Science and Technology at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].{{R|\"Freelance\"}}\n\nBecker joined the California Quantum Interpretation Network, \"a research collaboration among faculty and staff at multiple UC campuses and other universities across California, focusing on the interpretation of quantum physics.\"{{R|\"Center for Science\"}}\n\n== ''What is Real?'' ==\nIn 2016, Becker received a grant from the [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation]] to write a book.{{R|\"Sloane\"}} The resulting work, ''What is Real?'' (2018),{{R|\"Center for Science\"}} focused on the question of what exactly quantum physics says about the nature of reality.\n\n{{block quote| Despite the fact that every physicist agrees that quantum physics works, a bitter debate has raged over its meaning for the past ninety years, since the theory was first developed.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Becker |first1=Adam |title=What is Real? |date=2018 |publisher=Basic Books |location=New York |isbn=978-0-465-09605-3 |page=3}}</ref>}}\n\nThe book deals with the personalities behind the competing interpretations of quantum physics as well as the historical factors that influenced the debate\u2014factors such as military spending on physics research due to [[World War II]], the [[Cold War]] ethos that caused the eschewing of physicists thought to be [[Marxism|Marxist]], the assumed infallibility of [[John von Neumann]], the sexism that quashed the work of [[Grete Hermann]] the female mathematician who first spotted von Neumann's error, and the sway of prominent philosophical schools of the period, like the [[logical positivists]] of the [[Vienna Circle]]. [[Niels Bohr]] looms large in the book as the charismatic figure whose stature and obtuse writing style made it hard for alternate interpretations to be voiced. The book also challenges the popular portrayal of Albert Einstein as a behind-the-times thinker who couldn't accept the new paradigm. Becker argues that Einstein's [[thought experiments]] aimed at quantum dynamics are not stodgy quibbles with the seeming randomness of quantum physics, as characterized by the popularity of the quote that \"God does not play dice\".  Rather, Einstein's thought experiments are apt critiques of [[action at a distance]].\n\nThe book was reviewed by the ''New York Times,'' ''New York Review of Books'', ''Science'' and ''New Scientist'', among others.{{R|\"NYT\"}} {{R|\"NYREVIEW\"}} {{R|\"Publishers Weekly\"}}{{R|\"Science\"}}{{R|\"New Scientist\"}}{{R|\"Physics World2\"}}{{R|\"Boston\"}} In ''Physics Today'', David Wallace called the book \"a superb contribution both to popular understanding of quantum theory and to ongoing debates among experts.\"{{R|\"Physics Today\"}} In the ''Wall Street Journal,'' Andrew Crumey said, \"Adam Becker tells a fascinating if complex story of quantum dissidents.\"{{R|\"Wall Street\"}} And in ''Nature,'' Ramin Skibba said ''\"What Is Real?'' is an argument for keeping an open mind. Becker reminds us that we need humility as we investigate the myriad interpretations and narratives that explain the same data.\"{{R|\"Nature\"}} The book was among the finalists for the [[PEN/E. O. Wilson Literary Science Writing Award]] and ''[[Physics World]]'' magazine's Book of the Year.{{R|\"EO Wilson\"}}{{R|\"Physics World\"}} Reviews in ''[[Science News]]'' and the ''[[American Journal of Physics]]'' were more negative, criticizing the book for historical inaccuracies and philosophical oversimplifications.{{R|\"Science News\"}}{{R|\"American Journal\"}} [[Sheldon Lee Glashow]] was also critical.{{R|\"Glashow\"}} In his blog, [[Peter Woit]] took issue with what he saw as Becker's vilification of Niels Bohr and endorsement of [[Hugh Everett]]'s [[Many-worlds interpretation]], to which Becker replied that he intended to do neither.{{R|\"Woit\"}}\n\n== Selected publications ==\n'''Books'''\n\n*{{Cite book|title=What is real? : the unfinished quest for the meaning of quantum physics|last=Becker|first=Adam|isbn=978-0-465-09605-3|edition=First|location=New York, NY|oclc=1015259283|date=March 20, 2018}}\n\n'''Articles and websites'''\n\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/05/books/review/einsteins-shadow-seth-fletcher-albert-einstein.html|title=From Black Holes to Breakfast, Three Books Show How Einstein's Legacy Lives On|last=Becker|first=Adam|date=2019-02-05|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-11-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}\n* {{Citation|last=Becker|first=Adam|url=https://www.bbc.com/reel/playlist/the-big-questions|title=The Big Questions|work=BBC Reel|publisher=BBC|language=en|access-date=2019-11-30}} (BBC animated video series)\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/earth/story/20150309-why-does-time-only-run-forwards|title=Why does time always run forwards and never backwards?|last=Becker|first=Adam|work=[[BBC]]|language=en|access-date=2019-11-30}}\n* {{Cite news|last=Becker|first=Adam|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/06/14/619979605/light-of-the-stars-looks-to-other-planets-to-illuminate-climate-change-on-earth|title='Light Of The Stars' Looks To Other Planets To Illuminate Climate Change On Earth|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-11-30}}\n* Scientific American: <nowiki>https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/the-difficult-birth-of-the-many-worlds-interpretation-of-quantum-mechanics/</nowiki>\n* New Scientist: <nowiki>https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg21929274-200-wormhole-entanglement-gives-space-time-the-bends/</nowiki>\n* NOVA: <nowiki>https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/article/quantum-gambling-and-the-nature-of-reality/</nowiki>\n* Interactive Description of Bell's Theorem: <nowiki>https://freelanceastro.github.io/bell/</nowiki>\n* Aeon:<nowiki>https://aeon.co/essays/a-fetish-for-falsification-and-observation-holds-back-science</nowiki>\n* Undark:<nowiki>https://undark.org/article/junk-science-or-real-thing-inference/</nowiki>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"NYT\">\n{{cite web |last1= Gleick |first1= James |author-link= James Gleick |title=What Does Quantum Physics Actually Tell Us About the World? | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/books/review/adam-becker-what-is-real.html |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NYREVIEW\">\n{{cite web |last1=Albert |first1=David | author-link= David Albert|title=Quantum's Leaping Lizards |url=https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2018/04/19/quantums-leaping-lizards/ |website=NYBooks.com |publisher=New York Review of Books |accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Freelance\">\n{{cite web |last1=Becker |first1=Adam |title=Adam Becker |url=http://freelanceastrophysicist.com/ |website=Freelance Astrophysicist |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Basic Books\">\n{{cite web |title=Adam Becker |url=https://www.basicbooks.com/contributor/adam-becker/ |website=Basic Books |publisher=Basic Book |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Center for Science\">\n{{cite web |title=Adam Becker |url=http://cstms.berkeley.edu/people/adam-becker/ |website=CSTMS |publisher=University of California, Berkeley |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n<re