k |title= Box Hill |last= Tuson |first= Dan |year= 2013 |publisher= The National Trust |location= London |isbn= 978-1-84359-367-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Broadwood by Appointment: A History |last= Wainwright |first= D |year= 1982 |publisher= Quiller Press |location= London |isbn= 0-907621-10-4 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Warren |first1= S |title= 100 Greatest Cycling Climbs: A road cyclist's guide to Britain's hills |year= 2010  |publisher= Frances Lincoln |location= London |isbn= 978-0-7112-3120-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= London's Countryside : Geographical Field Work for Students and Teachers of Geography |url= https://archive.org/details/londonscountrysi0000wool |url-access= registration |last1= Wooldridge |first1= SW |last2= Hutchings |first2= GE |year= 1957 |publisher= Methuen |location= London |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Box Hill}}\n*[http://www.boxhillcommunity.com/ Box Hill community website]\n*[https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/box-hill Box Hill \u2013 National Trust]\n*[https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/betchworth-quarry-lime-kilns Betchworth Quarry \u2013 Surrey Wildlife Trust]\n*[https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/brockham-limeworks Brockham Quarry \u2013 Surrey Wildlife Trust]\n*[https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/headley-heath Headley Heath \u2013 National Trust]\n*[https://www.surreyoutdoorlearning.uk/facilities/high-ashurst High Ashurst \u2013 Surrey Outdoor Learning]\n*[https://www.field-studies-council.org/locations/juniperhall/ Juniper Hall \u2013 Field Studies Council]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title     = '''Nearest Settlements'''\n|Centre    = Box Hill\n|North     = Tyrrells Wood\n|Northeast = [[Headley, Surrey|Headley]]\n|East      = [[Colley Hill]]\n|Southeast = [[Betchworth]]\n|South     = [[Brockham]] \n|Southwest = [[Pixham]]<br>[[Dorking]]\n|West      = [[Westhumble]]\n|Northwest = [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham]]<br>[[Leatherhead]]\n}}\n{{Mole Valley}}\n{{Surrey Hills AONB}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hills of Surrey]]\n[[Category:National Trust properties in Surrey]]\n[[Category:Box Hill, Surrey]]\n[[Category:Climbs in cycle racing in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:RideLondon\u2013Surrey Classic]]\n[[Category:Cycle racing in England]]\n", "name_user": "Mertbiol", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eConservation:copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_Hill,_Surrey"}
{"title_page": "Bonaventure Plantation", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = Bonaventure Plantation\n| native_name= \n| former_names        = \n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| map_type            = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States]]\n| address             = \n| client              = \n| owner               = John Mullryne (original; 1762)<br />[[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.]] (1762\u20131782)<br />[[John Habersham]] (1782\u20131788)<br />[[Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1788\u2013unknown)<br />Edward Tattnall (''unknown''\u20131846)<br />Peter Wiltberger (1846\u20131907)\n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|32|3|05|N|81|2|22|W|region:US-GA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = 1762\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     = between 1804 and 1817\n| destruction_date    = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = \n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| references          = \n}}\n\n'''Bonaventure Plantation''' was a [[plantation]] in [[Savannah, Georgia]], United States, on land now occupied by Evergreen Cemetery and [[Bonaventure Cemetery]]. The site was {{convert|600|acre|km2}}, including a private cemetery, located on the [[Wilmington River (Georgia)|Wilmington River]], about {{convert|3.5|mi|km|abbr=off|0}} from the Savannah Colony.\n\n==History==\nThe plantation was founded in 1762<ref name=archive>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080614010507/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/6f01764198462d668525703b006b1481/48e128575f5994578525703500669825?OpenDocument Bonaventure Plantation] - SavannahGA.gov</ref> by Colonel John Mullryne, who had emigrated from England to [[Charleston, South Carolina]], initially, before moving north to Savannah.<ref name=jones>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1fExAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA540&lpg=PA540&dq=colonel+john+mulryne+savannah&source=bl&ots=Mfalti1wc_&sig=ACfU3U00vP0eRMZLT6FGp_T_8j78kdIjVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj188Pv1-joAhVBXc0KHQ1iCD4Q6AEwBHoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=colonel%20john%20mulryne%20savannah&f=false ''History of Savannah, Ga: From Its Settlement to the Close of the Eighteenth Century''], Charles Colcock Jones (D. Mason & Company, 1890)</ref> The property fell into the possession of the Tattnall family \u2014 [[Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1795\u20131871),<ref name=JT2>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/11367/josiah-tattnall Josiah Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> of Charleston, had married Mary, the youngest daughter of John and Claudia Mullryne.<ref name=jones/> Governor [[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.]] (1764\u20131804)<ref name=JT1>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7958532/josiah-tattnall Josiah Tattnall, Sr.] at FindAGrave.com</ref> was born at the plantation in 1764, a year after his brother, John Mullryne Tattnall.<ref name=archive/>\n\nThe first house was destroyed by a fire in 1771.<ref name=archive/> It was replaced by a brick mansion.<ref name=archive/>\n\nWhen Savannahians ousted and arrested royal Governor [[James Wright (governor)|James Wright]] in 1776, John Mullryne and Josiah Tattnall aided his escape through Bonaventure to a British naval vessel nearby.<ref>[https://www.telfair.org/article/bonaventure-a-historical-sketch/ \"BONAVENTURE: A HISTORICAL SKETCH\"] - [[Telfair Museums]], July 27, 2018</ref>\n\nIn 1779 the mansion was used as a hospital during the [[Siege of Savannah]].<ref name=archive/>\n\nThe Bonaventure estate was confiscated by the Revolutionary government in 1782 and sold at public auction to [[John Habersham]], a friend of the Tattnalls, who sold the property to Josiah Tattnall, Jr. in 1788. His wife, Harriett (1769\u20131802),<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66739544/harriet-tattnall Harriet Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> birthed nine children there between 1786 and 1801. Four of them died. Josiah died in 1804, two years after his wife. The orphaned children were raised in [[London]], England, by their grandparents.<ref name=archive/>\n\nIt is believed the mansion was destroyed between 1804 and 1817. [[John Berendt]] writes in his 1994 book ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]'' that a formal dinner party was in progress when one of the servants informed the host that the roof was ablaze and that nothing could be done to stop it. The host \"rose calmly, clinked his glass, and invited guests to pick up their dinner plates and follow him into the garden\", where they ate the remained of their meals in the glow of the flames.<ref>''Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' (John Berendt; Random House, 1994)</ref> Edward Tattnall (1788\u20131832),<ref name=EFT>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7440959/edward-fenwick-tattnall Edward Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> another son of Governor Tattnall, did not live at the mansion upon returning to Savannah and inheriting the estate.<ref name=archive/>\n\nThe estate remained in the Tattnall family until 1846, when Captain Peter Wiltberger became the new owner. His son, Major William H. Wiltberger, formed Evergreen Cemetery Company in 1849.<ref name=jones/>\n\n==Bonaventure Cemetery==\nThe following notable members of the Tattnall family are buried in [[Bonaventure Cemetery]]:\n\n*Harriett Tattnall (1769\u20131802)<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66739544/harriet-tattnall Harriett Tattnall] at FindaGrave.com</ref>\n*[[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.]] (1764\u20131804)<ref name=JT1/>\n*Claudia Tattnall (1789\u20131806)<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/81678288/claudia-tattnall Claudia Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref>\n*Edward Tattnall (1788\u20131832)<ref name=EFT/>\n*[[Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1795\u20131871)<ref name=JT2/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080614010507/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/6f01764198462d668525703b006b1481/48e128575f5994578525703500669825?OpenDocument Bonaventure Plantation] - SavannahGA.gov\n\n[[Category:Plantations in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:1762 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:History of Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = Bonaventure Plantation\n| native_name= \n| former_names        = \n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| map_type            = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States]]\n| address             = \n| client              = \n| owner               = John Mullryne (original; c. 1762)<br />[[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.]] (1762\u20131782)<br />[[John Habersham]] (1782\u20131788)<br />[[Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1788\u2013unknown)<br />Edward Tattnall (''unknown''\u20131846)<br />Peter Wiltberger (1846\u20131907)\n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|32|3|05|N|81|2|22|W|region:US-GA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = 1762\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     = between 1804 and 1817\n| destruction_date    = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = \n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| references          = \n}}\n\n'''Bonaventure Plantation''' was a [[plantation]] in [[Savannah, Georgia]], United States, on land now occupied by Evergreen Cemetery and [[Bonaventure Cemetery]]. The site was {{convert|600|acre|km2}}, including a private cemetery, located on the [[Wilmington River (Georgia)|Wilmington River]], about {{convert|3.5|mi|km|abbr=off|0}} from the Savannah Colony.\n\n==History==\nThe plantation was founded in 1762<ref name=archive>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080614010507/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/6f01764198462d668525703b006b1481/48e128575f5994578525703500669825?OpenDocument Bonaventure Plantation] - SavannahGA.gov</ref> by Colonel John Mullryne, who had emigrated from England to [[Charleston, South Carolina]], initially, before moving north to Savannah.<ref name=jones>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1fExAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA540&lpg=PA540&dq=colonel+john+mulryne+savannah&source=bl&ots=Mfalti1wc_&sig=ACfU3U00vP0eRMZLT6FGp_T_8j78kdIjVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj188Pv1-joAhVBXc0KHQ1iCD4Q6AEwBHoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=colonel%20john%20mulryne%20savannah&f=false ''History of Savannah, Ga: From Its Settlement to the Close of the Eighteenth Century''], Charles Colcock Jones (D. Mason & Company, 1890)</ref> The property fell into the possession of the Tattnall family \u2014 [[Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1795\u20131871),<ref name=JT2>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/11367/josiah-tattnall Josiah Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> of Charleston, had married Mary, the youngest daughter of John and Claudia Mullryne.<ref name=jones/> Governor [[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.]] (1764\u20131804)<ref name=JT1>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7958532/josiah-tattnall Josiah Tattnall, Sr.] at FindAGrave.com</ref> was born at the plantation in 1764, a year after his brother, John Mullryne Tattnall.<ref name=archive/>\n\nThe first house was destroyed by a fire in 1771.<ref name=archive/> It was replaced by a brick mansion.<ref name=archive/>\n\nWhen Savannahians ousted and arrested royal Governor [[James Wright (governor)|James Wright]] in 1776, John Mullryne and Josiah Tattnall aided his escape through Bonaventure to a British naval vessel nearby.<ref>[https://www.telfair.org/article/bonaventure-a-historical-sketch/ \"BONAVENTURE: A HISTORICAL SKETCH\"] - [[Telfair Museums]], July 27, 2018</ref>\n\nIn 1779 the mansion was used as a hospital during the [[Siege of Savannah]].<ref name=archive/>\n\nThe Bonaventure estate was confiscated by the Revolutionary government in 1782 and sold at public auction to [[John Habersham]], a friend of the Tattnalls, who sold the property to Josiah Tattnall, Jr. in 1788. His wife, Harriett (1769\u20131802),<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66739544/harriet-tattnall Harriet Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> birthed nine children there between 1786 and 1801. Four of them died. Josiah died in 1804, two years after his wife. The orphaned children were raised in [[London]], England, by their grandparents.<ref name=archive/>\n\nIt is believed the mansion was destroyed between 1804 and 1817. [[John Berendt]] writes in his 1994 book ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]'' that a formal dinner party was in progress when one of the servants informed the host that the roof was ablaze and that nothing could be done to stop it. The host \"rose calmly, clinked his glass, and invited guests to pick up their dinner plates and follow him into the garden\", where they ate the remained of their meals in the glow of the flames.<ref>''Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' (John Berendt; Random House, 1994)</ref> Edward Tattnall (1788\u20131832),<ref name=EFT>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7440959/edward-fenwick-tattnall Edward Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref> another son of Governor Tattnall, did not live at the mansion upon returning to Savannah and inheriting the estate.<ref name=archive/>\n\nThe estate remained in the Tattnall family until 1846, when Captain Peter Wiltberger became the new owner. His son, Major William H. Wiltberger, formed Evergreen Cemetery Company in 1849.<ref name=jones/>\n\n==Bonaventure Cemetery==\nThe following notable members of the Tattnall family are buried in [[Bonaventure Cemetery]]:\n\n*Harriett Tattnall (1769\u20131802)<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66739544/harriet-tattnall Harriett Tattnall] at FindaGrave.com</ref>\n*[[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.]] (1764\u20131804)<ref name=JT1/>\n*Claudia Tattnall (1789\u20131806)<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/81678288/claudia-tattnall Claudia Tattnall] at FindAGrave.com</ref>\n*Edward Tattnall (1788\u20131832)<ref name=EFT/>\n*[[Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1795\u20131871)<ref name=JT2/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080614010507/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/6f01764198462d668525703b006b1481/48e128575f5994578525703500669825?OpenDocument Bonaventure Plantation] - SavannahGA.gov\n\n[[Category:Plantations in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:1762 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:History of Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonaventure_Plantation"}
{"title_page": "2.0 (score)", "text_new": "{{About|the score of the film|the film itself|2.0 (film)|the soundtrack consisting of songs used in the film|2.0 (soundtrack)}}\n{{merge to|2.0 (soundtrack)|discuss=Talk:2.0 (soundtrack)#Merger proposal|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = 2.0 (Original Motion Picture Score)\n| type         = film score\n| artist       = [[A. R. Rahman]]\n| cover        = 2.0_film_score.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 29 June 2019\n| recorded     = 2015-2018\n| studio       = [[Panchathan Record Inn and AM Studios]], [[Chennai]]<br/>A.R. Studios, [[Mumbai]]<br/>A.R. Studios, [[London]]<br/>Panchathan Hollywood Studios, [[Los Angeles]]<ref name=\"Shankar\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/2018/nov/27/ar-rahmans-20-background-score-is-like-listening-to-batman-or-spidermans-bgm-shankar-1903931.html|title=AR Rahman's '2.0' background score is like listening to Batman or Spiderman's BGM: Shankar|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref>\n| genre        = [[Film score|Feature film score]],[[Post-industrial music|Post-industrial]], [[Experimental music|experimental]], [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n| length       = {{Duration|m=39|s=18}}\n| label        = Lyca Music<br/>[[Divo (record label)|Divo]]\n| producer     = A. R. Rahman\n| prev_title   = [[Sarvam Thaala Mayam]]\n| prev_year    = 2018\n| next_title   = [[Bigil]]\n| next_year    = 2019\n| misc         = {{external media\n| audio1 = {{YouTube|KH9_XiWauz4|Audio Jukebox}}\n}}\n| audio1       = \n}}\n'''''2.0''''' is the [[soundtrack]], to the 2018 Indian-[[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[Science fiction film|science fiction]] [[action film]] [[2.0 (film)|of the same name]]. The film score was composed by [[A. R. Rahman]] & [[Qutub-E-Kripa]], provided additional BGM for the film. Recording of the original score began in Abbey Road Studios, [[London]] and [[Panchathan Record Inn and AM Studios|Panchatan Hollywood Studios]], Los Angeles in 2016.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/rajinikanth-on-working-with-akshay-kumar-in-shankars-magnum-opus-hes-the-real-hero-and-villain-of-2-0-5542021.html|title=Rajinikanth on working with Akshay Kumar in Shankar's magnum opus: He's the real hero and villain of 2.0- Entertainment News, Firstpost|date=13 November 2018|website=Firstpost|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> Unlike previous projects, Rahman began finalising the original background score six months back prior to release because he felt that the scenes were very heavy and it needed a lot of work.<ref name=\"Shankar\"/>\n\nThe official film score consists of fifteen tracks with nearly a duration of nearly forty minutes. The film score was marketed and released on 29 June 2019.<ref name=\"Shankar\"/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{quote|''AR Rahman began the background score 6 months back since he felt the scenes were very heavy and it needed a lot of work. Now when I look at the background score, it looks like listening to Batman or Spiderman's background score. The complete credits for this project should be given to producer Subashkaran because no one else would have been ready to produce a big budget film like 2.0 except him''.<ref name=\"Shankar\"/><ref>{{Citation|title=2.0 Audio Launch - Part 7 {{!}} Rajinikanth, Akshay Kumar {{!}} Shankar {{!}} A.R. Rahman|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WJylBmPPuTI|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>|sign=Shankar in an interview, about 2.0, explaining the film's score|source=|align=right}}\nAccording to Rahman, he worked for a year on the soundtrack and background score.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} Highly [[Electronica music|electronical rock music]]<ref name=\"A.R.Rahman\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/arrahman/status/1144930393927192578?s=19|title=The Original Sound Track of 2.0 finally releasing this evening (as promised )|last=A.R.Rahman|date=29 June 2019|website=@arrahman|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{Citation|title=2.0 Audio Launch - Part 10 {{!}} Rajinikanth, Akshay Kumar {{!}} Shankar {{!}} A.R. Rahman|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oZ2DKhVr398|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref> has been used for this soundtrack. According to rahman, he worked 4 year on the soundtrack & background score. Highly [[Electronica music|electronical rock music]]<ref name=\"A.R.Rahman\"/><ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> has been used for this soundtrack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/arrahman/status/1144946365954437120?s=19|title=Here is the Original Soundtrack of 2.0 |last=A.R.Rahman|date=29 June 2019|website=@arrahman|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''2.0: Music from the Motion Picture''\n| title1 = Eerie Flapping\n| title2 = Its Over\n| title3 = Will You Believe\n| title4 = Shadow's Journey\n| title5 = We Need Chitti\n| title6 = You Are Next\n| title7 = Army Attack\n| title8 = Interval\n| title9 = Nila's Espionage\n| title0 = \n| title11 = Let The Game Begins\n| title12 = The Unknown\n| title13 = You Will Be Avenged\n| title14 = Replication\n| title15 = Pakshirajan's Story\n| all_writing = \n| length1 = 1:41\n| length2 = 0:18\n| length3 = 2:24\n| length4 = 1:32\n| length5 = 4:40\n| length6 = 2:56\n| length7 = 2:31\n| length8 = 3:40\n| length9 = 1:12\n| title10 = Grand Son\n| length10 = 1:00\n| total_length = 39:18\n| length11 = 2:46\n| length12 = 3:07\n| length13 = 2:02\n| length14 = 1:08\n| length15 = 6:31\n}}\n\n==Credits==\n{{cleanup section|date=November 2019|reason=Needs to be re-written}}\nScore Composed And Produced By : A.R. Rahman\n\nLead Orchestrators : Matt Dunkley\n\nAdditional Orchestrations : Richard Bronskill | Tony Blondal\n\nOrchestra : The Chamber Orchestra Of London\n\nOrchestra Contractor : Gareth Griffiths\n\nOrchestra Conductor : Matt Dunkley\n\nMusic Recorded : Geoff Foster\n\nPro Tools Recordist : John Barrett    \n  \nAssistant : George Oulton\n\nMusic Preparation : Dakota Music Service\n\nChoral Conductor: Arjun Chandy\n\nAdditional Arrangements and Programming : Ishaan Chhabra | T.R Krishna Chetan | Kumaran Sivamani | Jerry Silverster Vincent\n\nModular Synth Programming : Pawan CH\n\nMusic Supervission : Srinidhi Ventakesh\n\nMusic Mixed By : Geroff Foster\n\nAdditional Stereo Mix : P.A.Deepak\nMixing Assistant  : Riyasdeen Riyan\n\nSound Engineers : Suresh Permal | Karthik Sekaran (Panchathan Record Inn, Chennai)\n\nMastered By : Suresh Permal\n\nMFiT : Sivakumar S\n\nMusic Recorded at : Abbey Road Studios, London | Panchathan Record Inn, Chennai\n\nScore Co-Ordinators : Darrell Alexander | Gareth Griffiths\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2.0 (film)]]\n* [[2.0 (soundtrack)]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:2018 soundtracks]]\n[[Category:A. R. Rahman soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Tamil film soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Hindi film soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Telugu film soundtracks]]\n", "text_old": "{{mergeto|2.0 (soundtrack)|discuss=Talk:2.0 (soundtrack)#Merger proposal|date=October 2019}}\n{{About|the score of the film|the film itself|2.0 (film)|the soundtrack consisting of songs used in the film|2.0 (soundtrack)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = 2.0 (Original Motion Picture Score)\n| type         = film score\n| artist       = [[A. R. Rahman]]\n| cover        = 2.0_film_score.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 29 June 2019\n| recorded     = 2015-2018\n| studio       = [[Panchathan Record Inn and AM Studios]], [[Chennai]]<br/>A.R. Studios, [[Mumbai]]<br/>A.R. Studios, [[London]]<br/>Panchathan Hollywood Studios, [[Los Angeles]]<ref name=\"Shankar\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/2018/nov/27/ar-rahmans-20-background-score-is-like-listening-to-batman-or-spidermans-bgm-shankar-1903931.html|title=AR Rahman's '2.0' background score is like listening to Batman or Spiderman's BGM: Shankar|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref>\n| genre        = [[Film score|Feature film score]],[[Post-industrial music|Post-industrial]], [[Experimental music|experimental]], [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n| length       = {{Duration|m=39|s=18}}\n| label        = Lyca Music<br/>[[Divo (record label)|Divo]]\n| producer     = A. R. Rahman\n| prev_title   = [[Sarvam Thaala Mayam]]\n| prev_year    = 2018\n| next_title   = [[Bigil]]\n| next_year    = 2019\n| misc         = {{external media\n| audio1 = {{YouTube|KH9_XiWauz4|Audio Jukebox}}\n}}\n| audio1       = \n}}\n'''''2.0''''' is the [[soundtrack]], to the 2018 Indian-[[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[Science fiction film|science fiction]] [[action film]] [[2.0 (film)|of the same name]]. The film score was composed by [[A. R. Rahman]] & [[Qutub-E-Kripa]], provided additional BGM for the film. Recording of the original score began in Abbey Road Studios, [[London]] and [[Panchathan Record Inn and AM Studios|Panchatan Hollywood Studios]], Los Angeles in 2016.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/rajinikanth-on-working-with-akshay-kumar-in-shankars-magnum-opus-hes-the-real-hero-and-villain-of-2-0-5542021.html|title=Rajinikanth on working with Akshay Kumar in Shankar's magnum opus: He's the real hero and villain of 2.0- Entertainment News, Firstpost|date=13 November 2018|website=Firstpost|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> Unlike previous projects, Rahman began finalising the original background score six months back prior to release because he felt that the scenes were very heavy and it needed a lot of work.<ref name=\"Shankar\"/>\n\nThe official film score consists of fifteen tracks with nearly a duration of nearly forty minutes. The film score was marketed and released on 29 June 2019.<ref name=\"Shankar\"/>\n\n== Critical Reception ==\n{{quote|''AR Rahman began the background score 6 months back since he felt the scenes were very heavy and it needed a lot of work. Now when I look at the background score, it looks like listening to Batman or Spiderman's background score. The complete credits for this project should be given to producer Subashkaran because no one else would have been ready to produce a big budget film like 2.0 except him''.<ref name=\"Shankar\"/><ref>{{Citation|title=2.0 Audio Launch - Part 7 {{!}} Rajinikanth, Akshay Kumar {{!}} Shankar {{!}} A.R. Rahman|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WJylBmPPuTI|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>|sign=Shankar in an interview, about 2.0, explaining the film's score|source=|align=right}}\nAccording to Rahman, he worked for a year on the soundtrack and background score.{{cn|date=September 2019}} Highly [[Electronica music|electronical rock music]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/arrahman/status/1144930393927192578?s=19|title=The Original Sound Track of 2.0 finally releasing this evening (as promised )|last=A.R.Rahman|date=29 June 2019|website=@arrahman|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=2.0 Audio Launch - Part 10 {{!}} Rajinikanth, Akshay Kumar {{!}} Shankar {{!}} A.R. Rahman|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oZ2DKhVr398|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref> has been used for this soundtrack. According to rahman, he worked 4 year on the soundtrack & background score. Highly [[Electronica music|electronical rock music]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/arrahman/status/1144930393927192578?s=19|title=The Original Sound Track of 2.0 finally releasing this evening (as promised )|last=A.R.Rahman|date=29 June 2019|website=@arrahman|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{Citation|title=2.0 Audio Launch - Part 10 {{!}} Rajinikanth, Akshay Kumar {{!}} Shankar {{!}} A.R. Rahman|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oZ2DKhVr398|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref> has been used for this soundtrack. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/arrahman/status/1144946365954437120?s=19|title=Here is the Original Soundtrack of 2.0 |last=A.R.Rahman|date=29 June 2019|website=@arrahman|language=en|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Track Listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''2.0: Music from the Motion Picture''\n| title1 = Eerie Flapping\n| title2 = Its Over\n| title3 = Will You Believe\n| title4 = Shadow's Journey\n| title5 = We Need Chitti\n| title6 = You Are Next\n| title7 = Army Attack\n| title8 = Interval\n| title9 = Nila's Espionage\n| title0 = \n| title11 = Let The Game Begins\n| title12 = The Unknown\n| title13 = You Will Be Avenged\n| title14 = Replication\n| title15 = Pakshirajan's Story\n| all_writing = \n| length1 = 1:41\n| length2 = 0:18\n| length3 = 2:24\n| length4 = 1:32\n| length5 = 4:40\n| length6 = 2:56\n| length7 = 2:31\n| length8 = 3:40\n| length9 = 1:12\n| title10 = Grand Son\n| length10 = 1:00\n| total_length = 39:18\n| length11 = 2:46\n| length12 = 3:07\n| length13 = 2:02\n| length14 = 1:08\n| length15 = 6:31\n}}\n==Credits==\n{{cleanup section|date=November 2019|reason=Needs to be re-written}}\nScore Composed And Produced By : A.R. Rahman\n\nLead Orchestrators : Matt Dunkley\n\nAdditional Orchestrations : Richard Bronskill | Tony Blondal\n\nOrchestra : The Chamber Orchestra Of London\n\nOrchestra Contractor : Gareth Griffiths\n\nOrchestra Conductor : Matt Dunkley\n\nMusic Recorded : Geoff Foster\n\nPro Tools Recordist : John Barrett    \n  \nAssistant : George Oulton\n\nMusic Preparation : Dakota Music Service\n\nChoral Conductor: Arjun Chandy\n\n\nAdditional Arrangements and Programming : Ishaan Chhabra | T.R Krishna Chetan | Kumaran Sivamani | Jerry Silverster Vincent \n\nModular Synth Programming : Pawan CH\n\nMusic Supervission : Srinidhi Ventakesh \n\nMusic Mixed By : Geroff Foster\n\nAdditional Stereo Mix : P.A.Deepak\nMixing Assistant  : Riyasdeen Riyan\n\nSound Engineers : Suresh Permal | Karth